# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: melanoma
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:melanoma/8-oxoguanine] Increased concentrations of 8-oxoguanine in body fluids have been found to be associated with increased risk of mutagenesis and carcinogenesis.
[src:melanoma/8-oxoguanine] Care must be taken in the assay of 8-oxoguanine due to the ease with which it can be oxidised during extraction and the assay procedure.
[src:melanoma/8-oxoguanine] The role of the deoxyriboside form of 8-oxoguanine, 8-oxo-2'-deoxyguanosine (abbreviated 8-oxo-dG or 8-OHdG) in cancer and aging also applies to 8-oxoguanine.
[src:melanoma/8-oxoguanine] Oxoguanine glycosylase is employed in the removal of 8-oxoguanine from DNA by the process of base excision repair.
[src:melanoma/8-oxoguanine] As described in oxoguanine glycosylase, deficient expression of this enzyme causes 8-oxoguanine to accumulate in DNA.
[src:melanoma/8-oxoguanine] This accumulation may then lead upon replication of DNA to mutations including some that contribute to carcinogenesis.
[src:melanoma/8-oxoguanine] 8-oxoguanine is usually formed by the interaction of reactive oxygen species (ROS) with the guanine base in DNA under conditions of oxidative stress; as noted in the article about them, such species may have a role in aging and male infertility, and 8-oxoguanine can be used to measure such stress.
[src:melanoma/abim-foundation] The campaign identifies over 500 tests and procedures and encourages doctors and patients to discuss, research, and possibly get second opinions, before proceeding with them.
[src:melanoma/abim-foundation] To conduct the campaign, the ABIM Foundation asks medical specialty societies to make five to ten recommendations for preventing overuse of a treatment in their field.
[src:melanoma/abim-foundation] The foundation then publicizes this information, and the medical specialty societies disseminate it to their members.
[src:melanoma/abim-foundation] The campaign has garnered both praise and criticism, and some of its ideas have spread to other countries.
[src:melanoma/abim-foundation] It does not include evaluation of its effects on costs, on discussions or on medical outcomes.
[src:melanoma/abim-foundation] Some doctors have said they lack time for the recommended discussions.
[src:melanoma/abim-foundation] In 2002 the ABIM Foundation published *Medical professionalism in the new millennium: a Physician Charter*.
[src:melanoma/abim-foundation] The charter states that physicians have a responsibility to promote health equity when some health resources are scarce.
[src:melanoma/abim-foundation] As a practical way of achieving distributive justice, in 2010 physician Howard Brody recommended that medical specialty societies, being stewards of a field, ought to publish a list of five things which they would like changed in their field and publicize it to their members.
[src:melanoma/abim-foundation] In 2011, the National Physicians Alliance tested a project in which it organized the creation of some "top 5 lists".
[src:melanoma/abim-foundation] Analysis of the National Physician's Alliance project predicted that the health field could have saved US$6.8 billion in 2009 by cutting spending on the 15 services in the lists from three societies, out of total US health spending that year of US$2.5 trillion.
[src:melanoma/abim-foundation] US$5.8 billion of the savings were from one recommendation: using generic rather than brand name statin.
[src:melanoma/abim-foundation] Continuing this project, *Choosing Wisely* was created to organise the creation of more "lists of five," later ten, and their distribution to more physicians and patients.
[src:melanoma/abim-foundation] Executive boards of societies, with or without participation by members, identify practices which their field may overuse.
[src:melanoma/abim-foundation] Each recommendation in the program must have the support of clinical guidelines, evidence, or expert opinion.
[src:melanoma/abim-foundation] To participate in *Choosing Wisely*, each society developed list of tests, treatments, or services which that specialty commonly overuses.
[src:melanoma/abim-foundation] The society shares this information with their members, as well as organizations who can publicize to local community groups, and in each community patients and doctors can consider the information as they like.
[src:melanoma/abim-foundation] The ABIM Foundation gave grants to help societies participate.
[src:melanoma/abim-foundation] As of April 2018, there were 552 recommendations targeting a range of procedures to either question or avoid without special consideration.
[src:melanoma/abim-foundation] They can be searched online by key words, such as "back pain" but the numerous supporting footnotes on each recommendation are only in a pdf on the clinician page, without links to the papers.
[src:melanoma/abim-foundation] Between 2012 and 2023, more than 80 specialty societies highlighted examples.
[src:melanoma/abim-foundation] While these examples are no longer maintained and available on the website (www.choosingwisely.org), specialty societies are encouraged to publish individual lists.
[src:melanoma/abim-foundation] Many of these lists are accessible through https://www.aafp.org/pubs/afp/collections/choosing-wisely.html.
[src:melanoma/abim-foundation] In 2012 *The New York Times* said that the campaign was likely to "alter treatment standards in hospitals and doctors' offices nationwide" and one of their opinion writers said that many tests were unnecessary.
[src:melanoma/abim-foundation] CBS News said that "the evidence is on the initiative's side." *USA Today* noted that the campaign was "a rare coordinated effort among multiple medical societies".
[src:melanoma/abim-foundation] While expressing the need for evidence-based healthcare recommendations, in 2012 *The Economist* found the *Choosing Wisely* recommendations to be weak because they are not enforceable.
[src:melanoma/abim-foundation] In an editorial published in the *Southwest Journal of Pulmonary and Critical Care*, Richard Robbin and Allen Thomas expressed concern that the campaign could be used by payers to limit options for doctors and patients.
[src:melanoma/abim-foundation] In February 2013 the Robert Wood Johnson Foundation provided USD $2.5 million in funding for the campaign, saying that the foundation wanted to "help increase the tangible impact of the *Choosing Wisely* campaign".
[src:melanoma/abim-foundation] Based on what we have seen so far, we suspect that Choosing Wisely is much more about saving money than improving patient care.
[src:melanoma/abim-foundation] In 2015 a piece in *Newsweek* by Kurt Eichenwald described a controversy around the ABIM Foundation's lack of transparency about its finances and functioning.
[src:melanoma/abim-foundation] In 2016 campaign was described as an attempt to encourage doctors and patients to recognize the illusion of control or "therapeutic illusion" in choices to use treatments which have a basis outside of evidence-based medicine.
[src:melanoma/abim-foundation] In 2017 addiction specialists in Canada said the recommendation to wait for sobriety before treating depression was harmful and unjustified.
[src:melanoma/abim-foundation] A 2017 study reported that many patients and physicians found it challenging to use Choosing Wisely recommendations, particularly when the patient had symptoms, and the doctor recommended against a test.
[src:melanoma/abim-foundation] Barriers "included malpractice concern, patient requests for services, lack of time for shared decision making, and the number of tests recommended by specialists.
[src:melanoma/abim-foundation] Cedars–Sinai Medical Center in Los Angeles put 100 of the 552 Choosing Wisely items in its electronic medical records.
[src:melanoma/abim-foundation] These give warnings to doctors, but only after they have finished talking to patients and order a procedure or drug, so too late to have the recommended discussion.
[src:melanoma/abim-foundation] The *Choosing Wisely* campaign makes no provision to scientifically research its own efficacy, but academic centers are making plans to independently report on the impact of the campaign.
[src:melanoma/abim-foundation] The services targeted by the Choosing Wisely lists have broad variance in how much impact they can have on patients' care and costs.
[src:melanoma/abim-foundation] Doctors analyzed many services listed as low value by Choosing Wisely and other sources, and found that 25% or 42% of Medicare patients received at least one of these services in an average year, depending on definitions.
[src:melanoma/abim-foundation] The services represented 0.6% or 2.7% of Medicare costs and there was no significant pattern among types of physicians.
[src:melanoma/abim-foundation] The campaign has been cited as being part of a broader movement including many comparable campaigns.
[src:melanoma/abim-foundation] The German Network for Evidence Based Medicine considered adapting concepts from the program into the German healthcare system.
[src:melanoma/abim-foundation] In April 2014, Choosing Wisely Canada launched.
[src:melanoma/abim-foundation] Choosing Wisely Canada is organized by the Canadian Medical Association and the University of Toronto, and is chaired by Dr.
[src:melanoma/abim-foundation] English doctors "are worried how patients will perceive the initiative." In 2018, Norway launched *Gjør kloke valg* (lit.
[src:melanoma/abim-foundation] 'Make smart choices') modeled on the Choosing Wisely program.
[src:melanoma/abscess] An **abscess** is a collection of pus that has built up within the tissue of the body, usually caused by bacterial infection.
[src:melanoma/abscess] Signs and symptoms of abscesses include redness, pain, warmth, and swelling.
[src:melanoma/abscess] The swelling may feel fluid-filled when pressed.
[src:melanoma/abscess] The area of redness often extends beyond the swelling.
[src:melanoma/abscess] Carbuncles and boils are types of abscess that often involve hair follicles, with carbuncles being larger.
[src:melanoma/abscess] A cyst is related to an abscess, but it contains a material other than pus, and a cyst has a clearly defined wall.
[src:melanoma/abscess] Abscesses can also form internally on internal organs and after surgery.
[src:melanoma/abscess] They are usually caused by a bacterial infection.
[src:melanoma/abscess] Often many different types of bacteria are involved in a single infection.
[src:melanoma/abscess] In many areas of the world, the most common bacteria present are *methicillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus*.
[src:melanoma/abscess] Skin abscesses in particular are overwhelmingly caused by *S. aureus*.
[src:melanoma/abscess] Rarely, parasites can cause abscesses; this is more common in the developing world.
[src:melanoma/abscess] Diagnosis of a skin abscess is usually made based on what it looks like and is confirmed by cutting it open.
[src:melanoma/abscess] Ultrasound imaging may be useful in cases in which the diagnosis is not clear.
[src:melanoma/abscess] In abscesses around the anus, computer tomography (CT) may be important to look for deeper infection.
[src:melanoma/abscess] Standard treatment for most skin or soft tissue abscesses is cutting it open and drainage.
[src:melanoma/abscess] There appears to be some benefit from also using antibiotics.
[src:melanoma/abscess] A small amount of evidence supports not packing the cavity that remains with gauze after drainage.
[src:melanoma/abscess] Closing this cavity right after draining it rather than leaving it open may speed healing without increasing the risk of the abscess returning.
[src:melanoma/abscess] Sucking out the pus with a needle is often not sufficient.
[src:melanoma/abscess] Skin abscesses are common and have become more common in recent years.
[src:melanoma/abscess] Risk factors include intravenous drug use, with rates reported as high as 65% among users.
[src:melanoma/abscess] In 2005, 3.2 million people went to American emergency departments for abscesses.
[src:melanoma/abscess] In Australia, around 13,000 people were hospitalized in 2008 with the condition.
[src:melanoma/abscess] Abscesses may occur in any tissue, but most frequently within the skin surface (where they may be superficial pustules known as boils or deep skin abscesses), in the lungs, brain, teeth, kidneys, and tonsils.
[src:melanoma/abscess] Major complications may include spreading of the abscess material to adjacent or remote tissues, and extensive regional tissue death (gangrene).
[src:melanoma/abscess] The main symptoms and signs of a skin abscess are redness, heat, swelling, pain, and loss of function.
[src:melanoma/abscess] There may also be high temperature (fever) and chills.
[src:melanoma/abscess] If superficial, abscesses may be fluctuant when palpated; this wave-like motion is caused by movement of the pus inside the abscess.
[src:melanoma/abscess] An internal abscess is more difficult to identify and depends on the location of the abscess and the type of infection.
[src:melanoma/abscess] General signs include pain in the affected area, a high temperature, and generally feeling unwell.
[src:melanoma/abscess] Internal abscesses rarely heal themselves, so prompt medical attention is indicated if such an abscess is suspected.
[src:melanoma/abscess] An abscess can potentially be fatal depending on where it is located.
[src:melanoma/abscess] Risk factors for abscess formation include intravenous drug use.
[src:melanoma/abscess] Another possible risk factor is a prior history of disc herniation or other spinal abnormality, though this has not been proven.
[src:melanoma/abscess] Abscesses are caused by bacterial infection, parasites, or foreign substances.
[src:melanoma/abscess] Bacterial infection is the most common cause, particularly *Staphylococcus aureus*.
[src:melanoma/abscess] The more invasive methicillin-resistant *Staphylococcus aureus* (MRSA) may also be a source of infection, though it is much rarer.
[src:melanoma/abscess] Among spinal subdural abscesses, methicillin-sensitive *S. aureus* is the most common organism involved.
[src:melanoma/abscess] Rarely parasites can cause abscesses, and this is more common in the developing world.
[src:melanoma/abscess] Specific parasites known to do this include dracunculiasis and myiasis.
[src:melanoma/abscess] In immunocompromised people, and particularly those with AIDS, *Toxoplasma gondii* is a frequent cause of widespread abscesses throughout the body, including in the brain.
[src:melanoma/abscess] An abscess may form anywhere that bacteria can get through the skin, including insect bites, lacerations, puncture wounds, scrapes, IV injection sites, and other small surface-level injuries.
[src:melanoma/abscess] The overwhelming majority of skin abscesses are caused by *Staphylococcus aureus* (methicillin-susceptible or methicillin-resistant), with some studies showing over 90% of documented and cultured skin abscesses being caused by this organism.
[src:melanoma/abscess] Anorectal abscesses can be caused by non-specific obstruction and ensuing infection of the glandular crypts inside the anus or rectum.
[src:melanoma/abscess] Other causes include cancer, trauma, or inflammatory bowel diseases.
[src:melanoma/abscess] An *incisional abscess* develops as a complication secondary to a surgical incision.
[src:melanoma/abscess] It presents as redness and warmth at the margins of the incision with purulent drainage.
[src:melanoma/abscess] If the diagnosis is uncertain, the wound should be aspirated with a needle, with aspiration of pus confirming the diagnosis and availing for Gram stain and bacterial culture.
[src:melanoma/abscess] The cause can be from trauma, surgery, an infection, or a pre-existing condition.
[src:melanoma/abscess] An abscess is a buildup of pus surrounded by normal body tissue.
[src:melanoma/abscess] In most cases, abscesses are caused by an infectious species of bacteria, and they function to wall off the infection from uninfected tissues.
[src:melanoma/abscess] Organisms or foreign materials destroy the local cells, which results in the release of cytokines.
[src:melanoma/abscess] The cytokines trigger an inflammatory response, which draws large numbers of white blood cells to the area and increases the regional blood flow.
[src:melanoma/abscess] The final structure of the abscess is an abscess wall, or capsule, formed by adjacent healthy cells in an attempt to keep the pus from infecting neighboring structures.
[src:melanoma/abscess] However, such encapsulation tends to prevent immune cells from attacking bacteria in the pus or from reaching the causative organism or foreign object.
[src:melanoma/abscess] An abscess is a localized collection of pus (purulent inflammatory tissue) caused by suppuration buried in a tissue, an organ, or a confined space, lined by the pyogenic membrane.
[src:melanoma/abscess] Ultrasound imaging can help in a diagnosis.
[src:melanoma/abscess] Abscesses may be classified as either *skin abscesses* or *internal abscesses*.
[src:melanoma/abscess] Skin abscesses are common; internal abscesses tend to be harder to diagnose and more serious.
[src:melanoma/abscess] Skin abscesses are also called cutaneous or subcutaneous abscesses.
[src:melanoma/abscess] For those with a history of intravenous drug use, an X-ray is recommended before treatment to verify that no needle fragments are present.
[src:melanoma/abscess] If there is also a fever present in this population, infectious endocarditis should be considered.
[src:melanoma/abscess] Abscesses should be differentiated from empyemas, which are accumulations of pus in a preexisting, rather than a newly formed, anatomical cavity.
[src:melanoma/abscess] Other conditions that can cause similar symptoms include: cellulitis, a sebaceous cyst, and necrotising fasciitis.
[src:melanoma/abscess] Cellulitis typically also has an erythematous reaction, but does not confer any purulent drainage.
[src:melanoma/abscess] The standard treatment for an uncomplicated skin or soft-tissue abscess is the incision and drainage procedure.
[src:melanoma/abscess] There does not appear to be any benefit from also using antibiotics in most cases.
[src:melanoma/abscess] A small amount of evidence did not find a benefit from packing the abscess with gauze.
[src:melanoma/abscess] The abscess should be inspected to see if foreign objects are the cause, which may require their removal.
[src:melanoma/abscess] If foreign objects are not the cause, incising and draining the abscess is standard treatment.
[src:melanoma/abscess] In most cases, a localized injection of lidocaine and epinephrine precedes the incision, to suppress pain.
[src:melanoma/abscess] Most people with an uncomplicated skin abscess should not use antibiotics.
[src:melanoma/abscess] Antibiotics in addition to standard incision and drainage are recommended in persons with severe abscesses, many sites of infection, rapid disease progression, the presence of cellulitis, symptoms indicating bacterial illness throughout the body, or a health condition causing immunosuppression.
[src:melanoma/abscess] People who are very young or very old may also need antibiotics.
[src:melanoma/abscess] If the abscess does not heal only with incision and drainage, or if the abscess is in a place that is difficult to drain, such as the face, hands, or genitals, then antibiotics may be indicated.
[src:melanoma/abscess] In those cases of abscess which do require antibiotic treatment, *Staphylococcus aureus* bacteria are a common cause and an anti-staphylococcus antibiotic such as flucloxacillin or dicloxacillin is used.
[src:melanoma/abscess] The Infectious Diseases Society of America advises that the draining of an abscess is not enough to address community-acquired methicillin-resistant *Staphylococcus aureus* (MRSA).
[src:melanoma/abscess] In those cases, traditional antibiotics may be ineffective.
[src:melanoma/abscess] Alternative antibiotics effective against community-acquired MRSA often include clindamycin, doxycycline, minocycline, and trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole.
[src:melanoma/abscess] The American College of Emergency Physicians advises that typical cases of abscess from MRSA get no benefit from having antibiotic treatment in addition to the standard treatment.
[src:melanoma/abscess] Culturing the wound is not needed if standard follow-up care can be provided after the incision and drainage.
[src:melanoma/abscess] Performing a wound culture is unnecessary because it rarely gives information that can be used to guide treatment.
[src:melanoma/abscess] In North America, after drainage, an abscess cavity is usually packed, often with special iodoform-treated cloth.
[src:melanoma/abscess] This is done to absorb and neutralize any remaining exudate as well as to promote draining and prevent premature closure.
[src:melanoma/abscess] Prolonged draining is thought to promote healing.
[src:melanoma/abscess] The hypothesis is that though the heart's pumping action can deliver immune and regenerative cells to the edge of an injury, an abscess is by definition a void in which no blood vessels are present.
[src:melanoma/abscess] Packing is thought to provide a wicking action that continuously draws beneficial factors and cells from the body into the void that must be healed.
[src:melanoma/abscess] Discharge is then absorbed by cutaneous bandages, and further wicking is promoted by changing these bandages regularly.
[src:melanoma/abscess] However, evidence from emergency medicine literature reports that packing wounds after draining, especially smaller wounds, causes pain to the person and does not decrease the rate of recurrence, nor bring faster healing, or fewer physician visits.
[src:melanoma/abscess] More recently, several North American hospitals have opted for less-invasive loop drainage over standard drainage and wound packing.
[src:melanoma/abscess] In one study of 143 pediatric outcomes, a failure rate of 1.4% was reported in the loop group versus 10.5% in the packing group (P<.030), while a separate study reported a 5.5% failure rate among the loop group.
[src:melanoma/abscess] Closing an abscess immediately after draining it appears to speed healing without increasing the risk of recurrence.
[src:melanoma/abscess] This may not apply to anorectal abscesses, as while they may heal faster, there may be a higher rate of recurrence than those left open.
[src:melanoma/abscess] Appendiceal abscesses are complications of appendicitis, where there is an infected mass on the appendix.
[src:melanoma/abscess] This condition is estimated to occur in 2–10% of appendicitis cases and is usually treated by surgical removal of the appendix (appendicectomy).
[src:melanoma/abscess] Even without treatment, skin abscesses rarely result in death, as they will naturally break through the skin.
[src:melanoma/abscess] Other types of abscesses are more dangerous.
[src:melanoma/abscess] Brain abscesses may be fatal if untreated.
[src:melanoma/abscess] When treated, the mortality rate decreases to 5–10%, but it is higher if the abscess ruptures.
[src:melanoma/abscess] In 2005, in the United States, 3.2 million people went to the emergency department for an abscess.
[src:melanoma/abscess] In Australia, around 13,000 people were hospitalized in 2008 for the disease.
[src:melanoma/abscess] The Latin medical aphorism "*ubi pus, ibi evacua*" expresses "where there is pus, there evacuate it" and is classical advice in the culture of Western medicine.
[src:melanoma/abscess] Needle exchange programmes often administer or provide referrals for abscess treatment to injection drug users as part of a harm reduction public health strategy.
[src:melanoma/abscess] An abscess is so called "abscess" because there is an *abscessus* (a going away or departure) of portions of the animal tissue from each other to make room for the suppurated matter lodged between them.
[src:melanoma/abscess] The word carbuncle is believed to have originated from the Latin: *carbunculus*, originally a small coal; diminutive of *carbon-*, *carbo*: charcoal or ember, but also a carbuncle stone, "precious stones of a red or fiery colour", usually garnets.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] Susceptibility to acne is primarily genetic in 80% of cases.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] The roles of diet and cigarette smoking in the condition are unclear, and neither cleanliness nor exposure to sunlight are associated with acne.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] In both sexes, hormones called androgens appear to be part of the underlying mechanism, by causing increased production of sebum.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] Another common factor is the excessive growth of the bacterium *Cutibacterium acnes*, which is present on the skin.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] Treatments for acne are available, including lifestyle changes, medications, and medical procedures.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] The most effective medication is isotretinoin.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] Eating fewer simple carbohydrates such as sugar may minimize the condition.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] Treatments applied directly to the affected skin, such as azelaic acid, benzoyl peroxide, and salicylic acid, are commonly used.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] Antibiotics and retinoids are available in formulations that are applied to the skin and taken by mouth for the treatment of acne.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] However, resistance to antibiotics may develop as a result of antibiotic therapy.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] Several types of birth control pills help prevent acne in women.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] Medical professionals typically reserve isotretinoin pills for severe acne, due to greater potential side effects.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] Early and aggressive treatment of acne is advocated by some in the medical community to decrease the overall long-term impact on individuals.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] In 2015, acne affected approximately 633 million people globally, making it the eighth-most common chronic disease worldwide.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] Acne commonly occurs in adolescence and affects an estimated 80–90% of teenagers in the Western world.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] Some rural societies report lower rates of acne than industrialized ones.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] Children and adults may also be affected before and after puberty.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] Although acne becomes less common in adulthood, it persists in nearly half of affected people into their twenties and thirties, and a smaller group continues to have difficulties in their forties.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] There are six main types of acne: blackheads, whiteheads, papules, pustules, nodules, and cysts.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] The severity of acne vulgaris (Gr. ἀκμή, "point" + L.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] *vulgaris*, "common") can be classified as mild, moderate, or severe to determine an appropriate treatment regimen.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] There is no universally accepted scale for grading acne severity.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] The presence of clogged skin follicles (known as comedones) limited to the face with occasional inflammatory lesions defines mild acne.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] Moderate severity acne is said to occur when a higher number of inflammatory papules and pustules occur on the face, compared to mild cases of acne, and appear on the trunk of the body.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] Severe acne is said to occur when nodules (the painful 'bumps' lying under the skin) are the characteristic facial lesions, and involvement of the trunk is extensive.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] Large nodules were previously called cysts.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] The term *nodulocystic* has been used in the medical literature to describe severe cases of inflammatory acne.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] True cysts are rare in those with acne, and the term *severe nodular acne* is now the preferred terminology.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] Typical features of acne include increased secretion of oily sebum by the skin, microcomedones, comedones, papules, nodules (large papules), pustules, and often results in scarring.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] The appearance of acne varies with skin color.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] It may result in psychological and social problems.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] Acne scars are caused by inflammation within the dermis and are estimated to affect 95% of people with acne vulgaris.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] Abnormal healing and dermal inflammation create the scar.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] Scarring is most likely to take place with severe acne but may occur with any form of acne vulgaris.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] Acne scars are classified based on whether the abnormal healing response following dermal inflammation leads to excess collagen deposition or loss at the site of the acne lesion.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] Atrophic acne scars have lost collagen from the healing response and are the most common type of acne scar (accounting for approximately 75% of all acne scars).
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] Ice-pick scars, boxcar scars, and rolling scars are subtypes of atrophic acne scars.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] Boxcar scars are round or ovoid indented scars with sharp borders and vary in size from 1.5–4 mm across.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] Ice-pick scars are narrow (less than 2 mm across), deep scars that extend into the dermis.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] Rolling scars are broader than ice-pick and boxcar scars (4–5 mm across) and have a wave-like pattern of depth in the skin.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] Hypertrophic scars are uncommon and are characterized by increased collagen content after the abnormal healing response.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] They are described as firm and raised from the skin.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] Hypertrophic scars remain within the original margins of the wound, whereas keloid scars can form scar tissue outside of these borders.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] Keloid scars from acne occur more often in men and people with darker skin, and usually occur on the trunk of the body.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] After an inflamed nodular acne lesion resolves, it is common for the skin to darken in that area, which is known as postinflammatory hyperpigmentation (PIH).
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] The inflammation stimulates specialized pigment-producing skin cells (known as melanocytes) to produce more melanin pigment, which leads to the skin's darkened appearance.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] PIH occurs more frequently in people with darker skin color.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] Pigmented scar is a common term used for PIH, but is misleading as it suggests the color change is permanent.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] Often, PIH can be prevented by avoiding any aggravation of the nodule and can fade with time.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] However, untreated PIH can last for months, years, or even be permanent if deeper layers of skin are affected.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] Even minimal skin exposure to the sun's ultraviolet rays can sustain hyperpigmentation.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] Daily use of SPF 15 or higher sunscreen can minimize such a risk.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] Whitening agents like azelaic acid, arbutin or else may be used to improve hyperpigmentation.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] Risk factors for the development of acne, other than genetics, have not been conclusively identified.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] Possible secondary contributors include hormones, infections, diet, and stress.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] Studies investigating the impact of smoking on the incidence and severity of acne have been inconclusive.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] Cleanliness (hygiene) and sunlight are not associated with acne.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] Acne appears to be highly heritable; genetics explain 81% of the variation in the population.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] Studies performed in affected twins and first-degree relatives further demonstrate the strongly inherited nature of acne.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] Acne susceptibility is likely due to the influence of multiple genes, as the disease does not follow a classic (Mendelian) inheritance pattern.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] These gene candidates include certain variations in tumor necrosis factor-alpha (TNF-alpha), IL-1 alpha, and CYP1A1 genes, among others.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] The 308 G/A single nucleotide polymorphism variation in the gene for TNF is associated with an increased risk for acne.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] Acne can be a feature of rare genetic disorders such as Apert's syndrome.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] Severe acne may be associated with XYY syndrome.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] Hormonal activity, such as occurs during menstrual cycles and puberty, may contribute to the formation of acne.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] During puberty, an increase in sex hormones called androgens causes the skin follicle glands to grow larger and make more oily sebum.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] The androgen hormones testosterone, dihydrotestosterone (DHT), and dehydroepiandrosterone (DHEA) are all linked to acne.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] High levels of growth hormone (GH) and insulin-like growth factor 1 (IGF-1) are also associated with worsened acne.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] Both androgens and IGF-1 seem to be essential for acne to occur, as acne does not develop in individuals with complete androgen insensitivity syndrome (CAIS) or Laron syndrome (insensitivity to GH, resulting in very low IGF-1 levels).
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] Medical conditions that commonly cause a high-androgen state, such as polycystic ovary syndrome, congenital adrenal hyperplasia, and androgen-secreting tumors, can cause acne in affected individuals.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] Conversely, people who lack androgenic hormones or are insensitive to the effects of androgens rarely have acne.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] Pregnancy can increase androgen levels, and consequently, oily sebum synthesis.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] Acne can be a side effect of testosterone replacement therapy or anabolic steroid use.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] Over-the-counter bodybuilding and dietary supplements often contain illegally added anabolic steroids.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] The anaerobic bacterial species *Cutibacterium acnes* (formerly *Propionibacterium acnes*) contributes to the development of acne, but its exact role is not well understood.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] There are specific sub-strains of *C. acnes* associated with normal skin and others with moderate or severe inflammatory acne.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] It is unclear whether these undesirable strains evolve on-site or are acquired, or possibly both depending on the person.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] These strains have the capability of changing, perpetuating, or adapting to the abnormal cycle of inflammation, oil production, and inadequate sloughing of dead skin cells from acne pores.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] Some studies have explored a possible link between Demodex mites and acne, though findings remain inconclusive.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] It is unclear whether eradication of the mite improves acne.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] High-glycemic-load diets have been found to have different degrees of effect on acne severity.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] Multiple randomized controlled trials and nonrandomized studies have found a lower-glycemic-load diet to be effective in reducing acne.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] There is weak observational evidence suggesting that dairy milk consumption is positively associated with a higher frequency and severity of acne.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] Milk contains whey protein and hormones such as bovine IGF-1 and precursors of dihydrotestosterone.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] Studies suggest these components promote the effects of insulin and IGF-1 and thereby increase the production of androgen hormones, sebum, and promote the formation of comedones.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] Available evidence does not support a link between eating chocolate or salt and acne severity.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] Few studies have examined the relationship between obesity and acne.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] Vitamin B12 may trigger skin outbreaks similar to acne (acneiform eruptions), or worsen existing acne when taken in doses exceeding the recommended daily intake.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] There are few high-quality studies to demonstrate that stress causes or worsens acne.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] Despite being controversial, some research indicates that increased acne severity is associated with high stress levels in certain contexts, such as hormonal changes seen in premenstrual syndrome.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] Some individuals experience severe intensification of their acne when they are exposed to hot humid climates; this is due to bacteria and fungus thriving in warm, moist environments.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] This climate-induced acne exacerbation has been termed tropical acne.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] Mechanical obstruction of skin follicles with helmets or chinstraps can worsen pre-existing acne.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] However, acne caused by mechanical obstruction is technically not acne vulgaris, but another acneiform eruption known as acne mechanica.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] Several medications can also worsen pre-existing acne; this condition is the acne medicamentosa form of acne.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] Examples of such medications include lithium, hydantoin, isoniazid, glucocorticoids, iodides, bromides, and testosterone.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] When acne medicamentosa is specifically caused by anabolic–androgenic steroids it can simply be referred to as steroid acne.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] Genetically susceptible individuals can get acne breakouts as a result of polymorphous light eruption; a condition triggered by sunlight and artificial UV light exposure.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] This form of acne is called Acne aestivalis and is specifically caused by intense UVA light exposure.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] Affected individuals usually experience seasonal acne breakouts on their upper arms, shoulder girdle, back, and chest.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] The breakouts typically occur one-to-three days after exposure to intense UVA radiation.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] Unlike other forms of acne, the condition spares the face; this could possibly be a result of the pathogenesis of polymorphous light eruption, in which areas of the skin that are *newly* exposed to intense ultraviolet radiation are affected.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] Since faces are typically left uncovered at all stages of life, there is little-to-no likelihood for an eruption to appear there.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] Studies show that both polymorphous light eruption outbreaks and the acne aestivalis breakout response can be prevented by topical antioxidants combined with the application of a broad spectrum sunscreen.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] Acne vulgaris is a chronic skin disease of the pilosebaceous unit and develops due to blockages in the skin's hair follicles.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] Traditionally seen as a disease of adolescence, acne vulgaris is also observed in adults, including post-menopausal women.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] Acne vulgaris manifested in adult female is called *adult female acne* (AFA), defined as a chronic inflammatory disease of the pilosebaceous unit.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] The earliest pathologic change is the formation of a plug (a microcomedone), which is driven primarily by excessive growth, reproduction, and accumulation of skin cells in the hair follicle.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] In healthy skin, the skin cells that have died come up to the surface and exit the pore of the hair follicle.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] In people with acne, the increased production of oily sebum causes the dead skin cells to stick together.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] The accumulation of dead skin cell debris and oily sebum blocks the pore of the hair follicle, thus forming the microcomedone.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] The *C. acnes* biofilm within the hair follicle worsens this process.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] If the microcomedone is superficial within the hair follicle, the skin pigment melanin is exposed to air, resulting in its oxidation and dark appearance (known as a blackhead or open comedo).
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] In contrast, if the microcomedone occurs deep within the hair follicle, this causes the formation of a whitehead (known as a closed comedo).
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] The main hormonal driver of oily sebum production in the skin is dihydrotestosterone.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] Another androgenic hormone responsible for increased sebaceous gland activity is DHEA-S.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] The adrenal glands secrete higher amounts of DHEA-S during adrenarche (a stage of puberty), and this leads to an increase in sebum production.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] In a sebum-rich skin environment, the naturally occurring and largely commensal skin bacterium *C. acnes* readily grows and can cause inflammation within and around the follicle due to activation of the innate immune system.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] *C. acnes* triggers skin inflammation in acne by increasing the production of several pro-inflammatory chemical signals (such as IL-1α, IL-8, TNF-α, and LTB4); IL-1α is essential to comedo formation.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] This inflammatory cascade typically leads to the formation of inflammatory acne lesions, including papules, infected pustules, or nodules.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] If the inflammatory reaction is severe, the follicle can break into the deeper layers of the dermis and subcutaneous tissue and cause the formation of deep nodules.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] The involvement of AP-1 in the aforementioned inflammatory cascade activates matrix metalloproteinases, which contribute to local tissue destruction and scar formation.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] Along with the bacteria *C. acnes*, the bacterial species *Staphylococcus epidermidis* (*S. epidermidis*) also takes a part in the physiopathology of acne vulgaris.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] The proliferation of *S. epidermidis* with *C. acnes* causes the formation of biofilms, which blocks the hair follicles and pores, creating an anaerobic environment under the skin.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] This enables for increased growth of both *C. acnes* and *S. epidermidis* under the skin.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] The proliferation of *C. acnes* causes the formation of biofilms and a biofilm matrix, making it even harder to treat the acne.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] Acne vulgaris is diagnosed based on a medical professional's clinical judgment.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] The evaluation of a person with suspected acne should include taking a detailed medical history about a family history of acne, a review of medications taken, signs or symptoms of excessive production of androgen hormones, cortisol, and growth hormone.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] Comedones (blackheads and whiteheads) must be present to diagnose acne.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] In their absence, an appearance similar to that of acne would suggest a different skin disorder.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] Microcomedones (the precursor to blackheads and whiteheads) are not visible to the naked eye when inspecting the skin and require a microscope to be seen.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] Many features may indicate that a person's acne vulgaris is sensitive to hormonal influences.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] Historical and physical clues that may suggest hormone-sensitive acne include onset between ages 20 and 30; worsening the week before a woman's period; acne lesions predominantly over the jawline and chin; and inflammatory/nodular acne lesions.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] Several scales exist to grade the severity of acne vulgaris, but disagreement persists about the ideal one for diagnostic use.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] Cook's acne grading scale uses photographs to grade severity from 0 to 8, with higher numbers representing more severe acne.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] This scale was the first to use a standardized photographic protocol to assess acne severity; since its creation in 1979, the scale has undergone several revisions.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] The Leeds acne grading technique counts acne lesions on the face, back, and chest and categorizes them as inflammatory or non-inflammatory.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] Leeds scores range from 0 (least severe) to 10 (most severe) though modified scales have a maximum score of 12.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] The Pillsbury acne grading scale classifies the severity of the acne from grade 1 (least severe) to grade 4 (most severe).
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] Many skin conditions can mimic acne vulgaris, and these are collectively known as acneiform eruptions.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] Such conditions include angiofibromas, epidermal cysts, flat warts, folliculitis, keratosis pilaris, milia, perioral dermatitis, and rosacea, among others.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] Age is one factor that may help distinguish between these disorders.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] Skin disorders such as perioral dermatitis and keratosis pilaris can appear similar to acne but tend to occur more frequently in childhood.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] Rosacea tends to occur more frequently in older adults.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] Facial redness triggered by heat or the consumption of alcohol or spicy food is also more suggestive of rosacea.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] The presence of comedones helps health professionals differentiate acne from skin disorders that are similar in appearance.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p01] Chloracne and occupational acne due to exposure to certain chemicals & industrial compounds, may look very similar to acne vulgaris.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Many different treatments exist for acne.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] These include alpha hydroxy acid, anti-androgen medications, antibiotics, antiseborrheic medications, azelaic acid, benzoyl peroxide, hormonal treatments, keratolytic soaps, nicotinamide (niacinamide), retinoids, and salicylic acid.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Acne treatments work in at least four different ways, including the following: reducing inflammation, hormonal manipulation, killing *C. acnes*, and normalizing skin cell shedding and sebum production in the pore to prevent blockage.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Typical treatments include topical therapies such as antibiotics, benzoyl peroxide, and retinoids, and systemic therapies, including antibiotics, hormonal agents, and oral retinoids.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Recommended therapies for first-line use in acne vulgaris treatment include topical retinoids, benzoyl peroxide, and topical or oral antibiotics.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Procedures such as light therapy and laser therapy are not first-line treatments and typically have only an add on role due to their high cost and limited evidence.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Blue light therapy is of unclear benefit.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Medications for acne target the early stages of comedo formation and are generally ineffective for visible skin lesions; acne generally improves between eight and twelve weeks after starting therapy.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] People often view acne as a short-term condition, some expecting it to disappear after puberty.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] This misconception can lead to depending on self-management or problems with long-term adherence to treatment.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Communicating the long-term nature of the condition and better access to reliable information about acne can help people know what to expect from treatments.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] In general, it is recommended that people with acne do not wash affected skin more than twice daily.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] The application of a fragrance-free moisturizer to sensitive and acne-prone skin may reduce irritation.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Skin irritation from acne medications typically peaks at two weeks after onset of use and tends to improve with continued use.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Dermatologists recommend using cosmetic products that specifically say non-comedogenic, oil-free, and will not clog pores.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Acne vulgaris patients, even those with oily skin, should moisturize in order to support the skin's moisture barrier since skin barrier dysfunction may contribute to acne.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Moisturizers, especially ceramide-containing moisturizers, as an adjunct therapy are particularly helpful for the dry skin and irritation that commonly results from topical acne treatment.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Studies show that ceramide-containing moisturizers are important for optimal skin care; they enhance acne therapy adherence and complement existing acne therapies.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] In a study where acne patients used 1.2% clindamycin phosphate / 2.5% benzoyl peroxide gel in the morning and applied a micronized 0.05% tretinoin gel in the evening the overwhelming majority of patients experienced no cutaneous adverse events throughout the study.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] It was concluded that using ceramide cleanser and ceramide moisturizing cream caused the favorable tolerability, did not interfere with the treatment efficacy, and improved adherence to the regimen.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] The importance of preserving the acidic mantle and its barrier functions is widely accepted in the scientific community.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Thus, maintaining a pH in the range 4.5 – 5.5 is essential in order to keep the skin surface in its optimal, healthy conditions.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Causal relationship is rarely observed with diet/nutrition and dermatologic conditions.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Rather, associations have been found between diet and outcomes including disease severity and the number of conditions experienced by a patient.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Evidence is emerging in support of medical nutrition therapy as a way of reducing the severity and incidence of dermatologic diseases, including acne.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Researchers observed a link between high glycemic index diets and acne.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Dermatologists also recommend a diet low in simple sugars as a method of improving acne.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] As of 2014, the available evidence is insufficient to use milk restriction for this purpose.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Benzoyl peroxide (BPO) is a first-line treatment for mild and moderate acne due to its effectiveness and mild side-effects (mainly skin irritation).
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] In the skin follicle, benzoyl peroxide kills *C. acnes* by oxidizing its proteins through the formation of oxygen free radicals and benzoic acid.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] These free radicals likely interfere with the bacterium's metabolism and ability to make proteins.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Additionally, benzoyl peroxide is mildly effective at breaking down comedones and inhibiting inflammation.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Combination products use benzoyl peroxide with a topical antibiotic or retinoid, such as benzoyl peroxide/clindamycin and benzoyl peroxide/adapalene, respectively.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Topical benzoyl peroxide is effective at treating acne.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Side effects include increased skin photosensitivity, dryness, redness, and occasional peeling.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Sunscreen use is often advised during treatment, to prevent sunburn.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Lower concentrations of benzoyl peroxide are just as effective as higher concentrations in treating acne but are associated with fewer side effects.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Unlike antibiotics, benzoyl peroxide does not appear to generate bacterial antibiotic resistance.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Retinoids are medications that reduce inflammation, normalize the follicle cell life cycle, and reduce sebum production.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] They are structurally related to vitamin A.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Studies show dermatologists and primary care doctors underprescribe them for acne.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] The retinoids appear to influence the cell life cycle in the follicle lining.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] This helps prevent the accumulation of skin cells within the hair follicle that can create a blockage.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] They are a first-line acne treatment, especially for people with dark-colored skin.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Retinoids are known to lead to faster improvement of postinflammatory hyperpigmentation.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Topical retinoids include adapalene, retinol, retinaldehyde, isotretinoin, tazarotene, trifarotene, and tretinoin.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] They often cause an initial flare-up of acne and facial flushing and can cause significant skin irritation.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Generally speaking, retinoids increase the skin's sensitivity to sunlight and are therefore recommended for use at night.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Tretinoin is the least expensive of the topical retinoids and is the most irritating to the skin, whereas adapalene is the least irritating but costs significantly more.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Most formulations of tretinoin are incompatible for use with benzoyl peroxide.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Tazarotene is the most effective and expensive topical retinoid but is usually not as well tolerated.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] In 2019, a tazarotene lotion formulation, marketed to be a less irritating option, was approved by the FDA.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Retinol is a form of vitamin A that has similar but milder effects and is present in many over-the-counter moisturizers and other topical products.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Isotretinoin is an oral retinoid that is very effective for both severe nodular acne and moderate acne that is stubborn to other treatments.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] One to two months of use is typically adequate to see improvement.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Acne often resolves completely or is much milder after a 4–6 month course of oral isotretinoin.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] After a single round of treatment, about 80% of people report an improvement, with more than 50% reporting complete remission.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] About 20% of people require a second course, but 80% of those report improvement, resulting in a cumulative 96% efficacy rate.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] There are concerns that isotretinoin is linked to adverse effects, depression, suicidality, and anemia.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] There is no clear evidence to support some of these claims.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Isotretinoin has been found in some studies to be superior to antibiotics or placebo in reducing acne lesions.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] However, a 2018 review comparing inflammatory lesions after treatment with antibiotics or isotretinoin found no difference.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] The frequency of adverse events was about twice as high with isotretinoin use, although these were mostly dryness-related events.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] No increased risk of suicide or depression was conclusively found.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Medical authorities strictly regulate isotretinoin use in women of childbearing age due to its known harmful effects in pregnancy.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] For such a woman to be considered a candidate for isotretinoin, she must have a confirmed negative pregnancy test and use an effective form of birth control.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] In 2008, the United States started the iPLEDGE program to prevent isotretinoin use during pregnancy. iPLEDGE requires the woman to have two negative pregnancy tests and to use two types of birth control for at least one month before isotretinoin therapy begins and one month afterward.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] The effectiveness of the iPLEDGE program is controversial due to continued instances of contraception nonadherence.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] People may apply antibiotics to the skin or take them orally to treat acne.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] They work by killing *C. acnes* and reducing inflammation.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Although multiple guidelines call for healthcare providers to reduce the rates of prescribed oral antibiotics, many providers do not follow this guidance.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Oral antibiotics remain the most commonly prescribed systemic therapy for acne.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Widespread broad-spectrum antibiotic overuse for acne has led to higher rates of antibiotic-resistant *C. acnes* strains worldwide, especially to the commonly used tetracycline (e.g., doxycycline) and macrolide antibiotics (e.g., topical erythromycin).
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Therefore, dermatologists prefer antibiotics as part of combination therapy and not for use alone.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Commonly used antibiotics, either applied to the skin or taken orally, include clindamycin, erythromycin, metronidazole, sulfacetamide, and tetracyclines (e.g., doxycycline or minocycline).
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Doxycycline 40 milligrams daily (low-dose) appears to have similar efficacy to 100 milligrams daily and has fewer gastrointestinal side effects.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] However, low-dose doxycycline is not FDA-approved for the treatment of acne.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Antibiotics applied to the skin are typically used for mild to moderately severe acne.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Oral antibiotics are generally more effective than topical antibiotics and produce faster resolution of inflammatory acne lesions than topical applications.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] The *Global Alliance to Improve Outcomes in Acne* recommends that topical and oral antibiotics are not used together.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Oral antibiotics are recommended for no longer than three months, as antibiotic courses exceeding this duration are associated with the development of antibiotic resistance and show no clear benefit over shorter durations.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] If long-term oral antibiotics beyond three months are used, then it is recommended that benzoyl peroxide or a retinoid be used at the same time to limit the risk of *C. acnes* developing antibiotic resistance.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] The antibiotic dapsone is effective against inflammatory acne when applied to the skin.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] It is generally not a first-line choice due to its higher cost and a lack of clear superiority over other antibiotics.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Topical dapsone is sometimes a preferred therapy in women or for people with sensitive or darker-toned skin.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] It is not recommended for use with benzoyl peroxide due to the risk of causing yellow-orange skin discoloration with this combination.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Minocycline is an effective acne treatment, but it is not a first-line antibiotic due to a lack of evidence that it is better than other treatments and concerns about its safety compared to other tetracyclines.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Sarecycline is the most recent oral antibiotic developed specifically for the treatment of acne, and it is FDA-approved for the treatment of moderate to severe inflammatory acne in patients nine years of age and older.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] It is a narrow-spectrum tetracycline antibiotic that exhibits the necessary antibacterial activity against pathogens related to acne vulgaris and a low propensity for inducing antibiotic resistance.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] In clinical trials, sarecycline demonstrated clinical efficacy in reducing inflammatory acne lesions as early as three weeks and reduced truncal (back and chest) acne.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] In women, the use of combined birth control pills can improve acne.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] These medications contain an estrogen and a progestin.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] They work by decreasing the production of androgen hormones by the ovaries and by decreasing the free and hence biologically active fractions of androgens, resulting in lowered skin production of sebum and consequently reduce acne severity.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] First-generation progestins such as norethindrone and norgestrel have androgenic properties and may worsen acne.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Although oral estrogens decrease IGF-1 levels in some situations, which could theoretically improve acne symptoms, combined birth control pills do not appear to affect IGF-1 levels in fertile women.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Cyproterone acetate-containing birth control pills seem to decrease total and free IGF-1 levels.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Combinations containing third- or fourth-generation progestins, including desogestrel, dienogest, drospirenone, or norgestimate, as well as birth control pills containing cyproterone acetate or chlormadinone acetate, are preferred for women with acne due to their stronger antiandrogenic effects.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Studies have shown a 40 to 70% reduction in acne lesions with combined birth control pills.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] A 2014 review found that oral antibiotics appear to be somewhat more effective than birth control pills at reducing the number of inflammatory acne lesions at three months.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] However, the two therapies are approximately equal in efficacy at six months for decreasing the number of inflammatory, non-inflammatory, and total acne lesions.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] The authors of the analysis suggested that birth control pills may be a preferred first-line acne treatment over oral antibiotics in certain women due to similar efficacy at six months and a lack of associated antibiotic resistance.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] In contrast to combined birth control pills, progestogen-only birth control forms that contain androgenic progestins have been associated with worsened acne.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Antiandrogens such as cyproterone acetate and spironolactone can successfully treat acne, especially in women with signs of excessive androgen production, such as increased hairiness or skin production of sebum, or scalp hair loss.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Spironolactone is an effective treatment for acne in adult women.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Unlike combined birth control pills, it is not approved by the United States Food and Drug Administration for this purpose.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Spironolactone is an aldosterone antagonist and is a useful acne treatment due to its ability to additionally block the androgen receptor at higher doses.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Alone or in combination with a birth control pill, spironolactone has shown a 33 to 85% reduction in acne lesions in women.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] The effectiveness of spironolactone for acne appears to be dose-dependent.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] High-dose cyproterone acetate alone reportedly decreases acne symptoms in women by 75 to 90% within three months.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] It is usually combined with an estrogen to avoid menstrual irregularities and estrogen deficiency.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] The medication appears to be effective in the treatment of acne in males, with one study finding that a high dosage reduced inflammatory acne lesions by 73%.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] However, spironolactone and cyproterone acetate's side effects in males, such as gynecomastia, sexual dysfunction, and decreased bone mineral density, generally make their use for male acne impractical.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Pregnant and lactating women should not receive antiandrogens for their acne due to a possibility of birth disorders such as hypospadias and feminization of male babies.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Women who are sexually active and who can or may become pregnant should use an effective method of contraception to prevent pregnancy while taking an antiandrogen.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Antiandrogens are often combined with birth control pills for this reason, which can result in additive efficacy.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] The FDA added a black-box warning to spironolactone about possible tumor risks based on preclinical research with very high doses (>100-fold clinical doses) and cautioned that unnecessary use of the medication should be avoided.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] However, several large epidemiological studies subsequently found no greater risk of tumors in association with spironolactone in humans.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Conversely, strong associations of cyproterone acetate with certain brain tumors have been discovered and its use has been restricted.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] The brain tumor risk with cyproterone acetate is due to its strong progestogenic actions and is not related to antiandrogenic activity nor shared by other antiandrogens.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Flutamide, a pure antagonist of the androgen receptor, is effective in treating acne in women.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] It appears to reduce acne symptoms by 80 to 90% even at low doses, with several studies showing complete acne clearance.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] In one study, flutamide decreased acne scores by 80% within three months, whereas spironolactone decreased symptoms by only 40% in the same period.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] In a large long-term study, 97% of women reported satisfaction with the control of their acne with flutamide.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Although effective, flutamide has a risk of serious liver toxicity, and cases of death in women taking even low doses of the medication to treat androgen-dependent skin and hair conditions have occurred.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] As such, the use of flutamide for acne has become increasingly limited, and it has been argued that continued use of flutamide for such purposes is unethical.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Bicalutamide, a pure androgen receptor antagonist with the same mechanism as flutamide and with comparable or superior antiandrogenic efficacy but with a far lower risk of liver toxicity, is an alternative option to flutamide in the treatment of androgen-dependent skin and hair conditions in women.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Clascoterone is a topical antiandrogen that has demonstrated effectiveness in the treatment of acne in both males and females and was approved for clinical use for this indication in August 2020.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] It has shown no systemic absorption or associated antiandrogenic side effects.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] In a small direct head-to-head comparison, clascoterone showed greater effectiveness than topical isotretinoin.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] 5α-Reductase inhibitors such as finasteride and dutasteride may be useful for the treatment of acne in both males and females but have not been adequately evaluated for this purpose.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Moreover, 5α-reductase inhibitors have a strong potential for producing birth defects in male babies and this limits their use in women.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] However, 5α-reductase inhibitors are frequently used to treat excessive facial/body hair in women and can be combined with birth control pills to prevent pregnancy.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] There is no evidence as of 2010 to support the use of cimetidine or ketoconazole in the treatment of acne.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Hormone therapy is effective for acne both in women with hyperandrogenism and in women with normal androgen levels.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Azelaic acid is effective for mild to moderate acne when applied topically at a 15–20% concentration.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Treatment twice daily for six months is necessary, and is as effective as topical benzoyl peroxide 5%, isotretinoin 0.05%, and erythromycin 2%.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Azelaic acid is an effective acne treatment due to its ability to reduce skin cell accumulation in the follicle and its antibacterial and anti-inflammatory properties.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] It has a slight skin-lightening effect due to its ability to inhibit melanin synthesis.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Therefore, it is useful in treating individuals with acne who are also affected by post-inflammatory hyperpigmentation.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] It is less effective and more expensive than retinoids.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Azelaic acid also led to worse treatment response when compared to benzoyl peroxide.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] When compared to tretinoin, azelaic acid makes little or no treatment response.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Salicylic acid is a topically applied beta-hydroxy acid that stops bacteria from reproducing and has keratolytic properties.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] It is less effective than retinoid therapy.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Salicylic acid opens obstructed skin pores and promotes the shedding of epithelial skin cells.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Dry skin is the most commonly seen side effect with topical application, though darkening of the skin can occur in individuals with darker skin types.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Topical and oral preparations of nicotinamide (the amide form of vitamin B3) are alternative medical treatments.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Topical and oral preparations of zinc are suggested treatments for acne; evidence to support their use for this purpose is limited.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Zinc's capacities to reduce inflammation and sebum production as well as inhibit *C. acnes* growth are its proposed mechanisms for improving acne.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Antihistamines may improve symptoms among those already taking isotretinoin due to their anti-inflammatory properties and their ability to suppress sebum production.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Hydroquinone lightens the skin when applied topically by inhibiting tyrosinase, the enzyme responsible for converting the amino acid tyrosine to the skin pigment melanin, and is used to treat acne-associated post-inflammatory hyperpigmentation.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] By interfering with the production of melanin in the epidermis, hydroquinone leads to less hyperpigmentation as darkened skin cells are naturally shed over time.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Improvement in skin hyperpigmentation is typically seen within six months when used twice daily.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Hydroquinone is ineffective for hyperpigmentation affecting deeper layers of skin such as the dermis.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] The use of a sunscreen with SPF 15 or higher in the morning with reapplication every two hours is recommended when using hydroquinone.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Its application only to affected areas lowers the risk of lightening the color of normal skin but can lead to a temporary ring of lightened skin around the hyperpigmented area.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Hydroquinone is generally well-tolerated; side effects are typically mild (e.g., skin irritation) and occur with the use of a higher than the recommended 4% concentration.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Most preparations contain the preservative sodium metabisulfite, which has been linked to rare cases of allergic reactions, including anaphylaxis and severe asthma exacerbations in susceptible people.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] In extremely rare cases, the frequent and improper application of high-dose hydroquinone has been associated with a systemic condition known as exogenous ochronosis (skin discoloration and connective tissue damage from the accumulation of homogentisic acid).
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Combination therapy—using medications of different classes together, each with a different mechanism of action—has been demonstrated to be a more effective approach to acne treatment than monotherapy.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] The use of topical benzoyl peroxide and antibiotics together is more effective than antibiotics alone.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Similarly, using a topical retinoid with an antibiotic clears acne lesions faster than the use of antibiotics alone.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Frequently used combinations include the following: antibiotic and benzoyl peroxide, antibiotic and topical retinoid, or topical retinoid and benzoyl peroxide.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Dermatologists generally prefer combining benzoyl peroxide with a retinoid over the combination of a topical antibiotic with a retinoid.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Both regimens are effective, but benzoyl peroxide does not lead to antibiotic resistance.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Although sebaceous gland activity in the skin increases during the late stages of pregnancy, pregnancy has not been reliably associated with worsened acne severity.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] In general, topically applied medications are considered the first-line approach to acne treatment during pregnancy, as they have little systemic absorption and are therefore unlikely to harm a developing fetus.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Highly recommended therapies include topically applied benzoyl peroxide (pregnancy category C) and azelaic acid (category B).
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Prolonged use of salicylic acid over significant areas of the skin or under occlusive (sealed) dressings is not recommended as these methods increase systemic absorption and the potential for fetal harm.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Tretinoin (category C) and adapalene (category C) are very poorly absorbed, but certain studies have suggested teratogenic effects in the first trimester.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] The data examining the association between maternal topical retinoid exposure in the first trimester of pregnancy and adverse pregnancy outcomes is limited.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] A systematic review of observational studies concluded that such exposure does not appear to increase the risk of major birth defects, miscarriages, stillbirths, premature births, or low birth weight.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Similarly, in studies examining the effects of topical retinoids during pregnancy, fetal harm has not been seen in the second and third trimesters.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Nevertheless, since rare harms from topical retinoids are not ruled out, they are not recommended for use during pregnancy due to persistent safety concerns.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Retinoids contraindicated for use during pregnancy include the topical retinoid tazarotene, and oral retinoids isotretinoin and acitretin (all category X).
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Spironolactone is relatively contraindicated for use during pregnancy due to its antiandrogen effects.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Finasteride is not recommended as it is highly teratogenic.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Topical antibiotics deemed safe during pregnancy include clindamycin, erythromycin, and metronidazole (all category B), due to negligible systemic absorption.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Nadifloxacin and dapsone (category C) are other topical antibiotics that may be used to treat acne in pregnant women but have received less study.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] No adverse fetal events have been reported from the topical use of dapsone.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] If retinoids are used there is a high risk of abnormalities occurring in the developing fetus; women of childbearing age are therefore required to use effective birth control if retinoids are used to treat acne.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Oral antibiotics deemed safe for pregnancy (all category B) include azithromycin, cephalosporins, and penicillins.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Tetracyclines (category D) are contraindicated during pregnancy as they are known to deposit in developing fetal teeth, resulting in yellow discoloration and thinned tooth enamel.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Their use during pregnancy has been associated with the development of acute fatty liver of pregnancy and is further avoided for this reason.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Limited evidence supports comedo extraction, but it is an option for comedones that do not improve with standard treatment.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Another procedure for immediate relief is the injection of a corticosteroid into an inflamed acne comedo.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Electrocautery and electrofulguration are effective alternative treatments for comedones.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Light therapy is a treatment method that involves delivering certain specific wavelengths of light to an area of skin affected by acne.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Both regular and laser light have been used.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] The evidence for light therapy as a treatment for acne is weak and inconclusive.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Various light therapies appear to provide a short-term benefit, but data for long-term outcomes, and outcomes in those with severe acne, are sparse; it may have a role for individuals whose acne has been resistant to topical medications.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] A 2016 meta-analysis was unable to conclude whether light therapies were more beneficial than placebo or no treatment, nor the duration of benefit.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] When regular light is used immediately following the application of a sensitizing substance to the skin such as aminolevulinic acid or methyl aminolevulinate, the treatment is referred to as photodynamic therapy (PDT).
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] PDT has the most supporting evidence of all light therapy modalities.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] PDT treats acne by using various forms of light (e.g., blue light or red light) that preferentially target the pilosebaceous unit.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Once the light activates the sensitizing substance, this generates free radicals and reactive oxygen species in the skin, which purposefully damage the sebaceous glands and kill *C. acnes* bacteria.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Many different types of nonablative lasers (i.e., lasers that do not vaporize the top layer of the skin but rather induce a physiologic response in the skin from the light) have been used to treat acne, including those that use infrared wavelengths of light.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Ablative lasers (such as CO2 and fractional types) have also been used to treat active acne and its scars.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] When ablative lasers are used, the treatment is often referred to as laser resurfacing because, as mentioned previously, the entire upper layers of the skin are vaporized.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Ablative lasers are associated with higher rates of adverse effects compared with non-ablative lasers, with examples being post-inflammatory hyperpigmentation, persistent facial redness, and persistent pain.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Physiologically, certain wavelengths of light, used with or without accompanying topical chemicals, are thought to kill bacteria and decrease the size and activity of the glands that produce sebum.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Disadvantages of light therapy can include its cost, the need for multiple visits, the time required to complete the procedure(s), and pain associated with some of the treatment modalities.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Typical side effects include skin peeling, temporary reddening of the skin, swelling, and post-inflammatory hyperpigmentation.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Dermabrasion is an effective therapeutic procedure for reducing the appearance of superficial atrophic scars of the boxcar and rolling varieties.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Ice-pick scars do not respond well to treatment with dermabrasion due to their depth.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] The procedure is painful and has many potential side effects such as skin sensitivity to sunlight, redness, and decreased pigmentation of the skin.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Dermabrasion has fallen out of favor with the introduction of laser resurfacing.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Unlike dermabrasion, there is no evidence that microdermabrasion is an effective treatment for acne.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Dermal or subcutaneous fillers are substances injected into the skin to improve the appearance of acne scars.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Fillers are used to increase natural collagen production in the skin and to increase skin volume and decrease the depth of acne scars.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Examples of fillers used for this purpose include hyaluronic acid; poly(methyl methacrylate) microspheres with collagen; human and bovine collagen derivatives, and fat harvested from the person's own body (autologous fat transfer).
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Microneedling is a procedure in which an instrument with multiple rows of tiny needles is rolled over the skin to elicit a wound healing response and stimulate collagen production to reduce the appearance of atrophic acne scars in people with darker skin color.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Notable adverse effects of microneedling include post-inflammatory hyperpigmentation and tram track scarring (described as discrete slightly raised scars in a linear distribution similar to a tram track).
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] The latter is thought to be primarily attributable to improper technique by the practitioner, including the use of excessive pressure or inappropriately large needles.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Subcision is useful for the treatment of superficial atrophic acne scars and involves the use of a small needle to loosen the fibrotic adhesions that result in the depressed appearance of the scar.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Chemical peels can be used to reduce the appearance of acne scars.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Mild peels include those using glycolic acid, lactic acid, salicylic acid, Jessner's solution, or a lower concentration (20%) of trichloroacetic acid.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] These peels only affect the epidermal layer of the skin and can be useful in the treatment of superficial acne scars as well as skin pigmentation changes from inflammatory acne.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Higher concentrations of trichloroacetic acid (30–40%) are considered to be medium-strength peels and affect the skin as deep as the papillary dermis.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Formulations of trichloroacetic acid concentrated to 50% or more are considered to be deep chemical peels.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Medium-strength and deep-strength chemical peels are more effective for deeper atrophic scars but are more likely to cause side effects such as skin pigmentation changes, infection, and small white superficial cysts known as milia.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Researchers are investigating complementary therapies as treatment for people with acne.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Low-quality evidence suggests topical application of tea tree oil or bee venom may reduce the total number of skin lesions in those with acne.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Tea tree oil appears to be approximately as effective as benzoyl peroxide or salicylic acid but is associated with allergic contact dermatitis.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Proposed mechanisms for tea tree oil's anti-acne effects include antibacterial action against *C. acnes* and anti-inflammatory properties.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Numerous other plant-derived therapies have demonstrated positive effects against acne (e.g., basil oil; oligosaccharides from seaweed; however, few well-done studies have examined their use for this purpose.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] There is a lack of high-quality evidence for the use of acupuncture, herbal medicine, or cupping therapy for acne.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Many over-the-counter treatments in many forms are available, which are often known as cosmeceuticals.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Certain types of makeup may be useful to mask acne.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] In those with oily skin, a water-based product is often preferred.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Acne usually improves around the age of 20 but may persist into adulthood.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Rare complications from acne or its treatment include the formation of pyogenic granulomas, osteoma cutis, and acne with facial edema.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Early and aggressive treatment of acne is advocated by some in the medical community to reduce the chances of these poor outcomes.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] There is good evidence to support the idea that acne and associated scarring negatively affect a person's psychological state, worsen mood, lower self-esteem, and are associated with a higher risk of anxiety disorders, depression, and suicidal thoughts.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Misperceptions about acne's causative and aggravating factors are common, and people with acne often blame themselves, and others often blame those with acne for their condition.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Such blame can worsen the affected person's sense of self-esteem.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Until the 20th century, even among dermatologists, the list of causes was believed to include excessive sexual thoughts and masturbation.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Dermatology's association with sexually transmitted infections, especially syphilis, contributed to the stigma.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Another psychological complication of acne vulgaris is acne excoriée, which occurs when a person persistently picks and scratches pimples, irrespective of the severity of their acne.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] This can lead to significant scarring, changes in the affected person's skin pigmentation, and a cyclic worsening of the affected person's anxiety about their appearance.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Globally, acne affects approximately 650 million people, or about 9.4% of the population, as of 2010.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] It affects nearly 90% of people in Western societies during their teenage years, but can occur before adolescence and may persist into adulthood.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] While acne that first develops between the ages of 21 and 25 is uncommon, it affects 54% of women and 40% of men older than 25 years of age and has a lifetime prevalence of 85%.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] About 20% of those affected have moderate or severe cases.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] It is slightly more common in females than males (9.8% versus 9.0%).
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] In those over 40 years old, 1% of males and 5% of females still have problems.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Rates appear to be lower in rural societies.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] While some research has found it affects people of all ethnic groups, acne may not occur in the non-Westernized peoples of Papua New Guinea and Paraguay.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Acne affects 40–50 million people in the United States (16%) and approximately 3–5 million in Australia (23%).
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Severe acne tends to be more common in people of Caucasian or Amerindian descent than in people of African descent.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Historical records indicate that pharaohs had acne, which may be the earliest known reference to the disease.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Sulfur's usefulness as a topical remedy for acne dates back to at least the reign of Cleopatra (69–30 BCE).
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] The sixth-century Greek physician Aëtius of Amida reportedly coined the term "*ionthos*" (ίονθωξ,) or "*acnae*", which seems to be a reference to facial skin lesions that occur during "the 'acme' of life" (puberty).
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] In the 16th century, the French physician and botanist François Boissier de Sauvages de Lacroix provided one of the earlier descriptions of acne.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] He used the term "psydracia achne" to describe small, red, and hard tubercles that altered a person's facial appearance during adolescence and were neither itchy nor painful.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] The recognition and characterization of acne progressed in 1776 when Josef Plenck (an Austrian physician) published a book that proposed the novel concept of classifying skin diseases by their elementary (initial) lesions.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] In 1808 the English dermatologist Robert Willan refined Plenck's work by providing the first detailed descriptions of several skin disorders using morphologic terminology that remains in use today.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Thomas Bateman continued and expanded on Robert Willan's work as his student and provided the first descriptions and illustrations of acne accepted as accurate by modern dermatologists.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Erasmus Wilson, in 1842, was the first to make the distinction between acne vulgaris and rosacea.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] The first professional medical monograph dedicated entirely to acne was written by Lucius Duncan Bulkley and published in New York in 1885.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Scientists initially hypothesized that acne represented a disease of the skin's hair follicle, and occurred due to blockage of the pore by sebum.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] During the 1880s, they observed bacteria by microscopy in skin samples from people with acne.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Investigators believed the bacteria caused comedones, sebum production, and ultimately acne.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] During the mid-twentieth century, dermatologists realized that no single hypothesized factor (sebum, bacteria, or excess keratin) fully accounted for the disease in its entirety.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] This led to the current understanding that acne could be explained by a sequence of related events, beginning with blockage of the skin follicle by excessive dead skin cells, followed by bacterial invasion of the hair follicle pore, changes in sebum production, and inflammation.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] The approach to acne treatment underwent significant changes during the twentieth century.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Retinoids became a medical treatment for acne in 1943.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Benzoyl peroxide was first proposed as a treatment in 1958 and remains a staple of acne treatment.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] The introduction of oral tetracycline antibiotics (such as minocycline) modified acne treatment in the 1950s.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] These reinforced the idea amongst dermatologists that bacterial growth on the skin plays an important role in causing acne.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Subsequently, in the 1970s, tretinoin (original trade name Retin A) was found to be an effective treatment.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] The development of oral isotretinoin (sold as Accutane and Roaccutane) followed.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] After its introduction in the United States in 1982, scientists identified isotretinoin as a medication highly likely to cause birth defects if taken during pregnancy.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] In the United States, more than 2,000 women became pregnant while taking isotretinoin between 1982 and 2003, with most pregnancies ending in abortion or miscarriage.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Approximately 160 babies were born with birth defects due to maternal use of isotretinoin during pregnancy.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Treatment of acne with topical crushed dry ice, known as cryoslush, was first described in 1907 but is no longer performed commonly.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Before 1960, the use of X-rays was also a common treatment.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] The costs and social impact of acne are substantial.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] In the United States, acne vulgaris is responsible for more than 5 million doctor visits and costs over US$2.5 billion each year in direct costs.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Similarly, acne vulgaris is responsible for 3.5 million doctor visits each year in the United Kingdom.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Sales for the top ten leading acne treatment brands in the US in 2015 amounted to $352 million.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Acne vulgaris and its resultant scars are associated with significant social and academic difficulties that can last into adulthood.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] During the Great Depression, dermatologists discovered that young men with acne had difficulty obtaining jobs.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Until the 1930s, many people viewed acne as a trivial problem among middle-class girls because, unlike smallpox and tuberculosis, no one died from it, and a feminine problem, because boys were much less likely to seek medical assistance for it.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] During World War II, some American soldiers in tropical climates developed such severe and widespread tropical acne on their bodies that they were declared medically unfit for duty.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Efforts to better understand the mechanisms of sebum production are underway.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] This research aims to develop medications that target and interfere with the hormones that are known to increase sebum production (e.g., IGF-1 and alpha-melanocyte-stimulating hormone).
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Other sebum-lowering medications such as topical antiandrogens, peroxisome proliferator-activated receptor modulators, and inhibitors of the stearoyl-CoA desaturase-1 enzyme are also a focus of research efforts.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Particles that release nitric oxide into the skin to decrease skin inflammation caused by *C. acnes* and the immune system have shown promise for improving acne in early clinical trials.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Another avenue of early-stage research has focused on how to best use laser and light therapy to selectively destroy sebum-producing glands in the skin's hair follicles to reduce sebum production and improve acne appearance.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] The use of antimicrobial peptides against *C. acnes* is under investigation as a treatment for acne to overcoming antibiotic resistance.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] In 2007, scientists reported the first genome sequencing of a *C. acnes* bacteriophage (PA6).
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] The authors proposed applying this research toward the development of bacteriophage therapy as an acne treatment to overcome the problems associated with long-term antibiotic use, such as bacterial resistance.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Oral and topical probiotics are under evaluation as treatments for acne.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Probiotics may have therapeutic effects for those affected by acne due to their ability to decrease skin inflammation and improve skin moisture by increasing the skin's ceramide content.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] As of 2014, knowledge of the effects of probiotics on acne in humans was limited.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Decreased levels of retinoic acid in the skin may contribute to comedo formation.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Researchers are investigating methods to increase the skin's production of retinoic acid to address this deficiency.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] A vaccine against inflammatory acne has shown promising results in mice and humans.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Some have voiced concerns about creating a vaccine designed to neutralize a stable community of normal skin bacteria that is known to protect the skin from colonization by more harmful microorganisms.
[src:melanoma/acne-vulgaris-p02] Acne can occur on cats, dogs, and horses.
[src:melanoma/acral-lentiginous-melanoma] Melanoma is a group of serious skin cancers that arise from pigment cells (melanocytes); acral lentiginous melanoma is a kind of lentiginous skin melanoma.
[src:melanoma/acral-lentiginous-melanoma] ALM makes up less than 5% of all melanomas, but is considered the most common subtype in people with darker skin and is rare in people with lighter skin types.
[src:melanoma/acral-lentiginous-melanoma] It is not caused by exposure to sunlight or UV radiation, and wearing sunscreen does not protect against it.
[src:melanoma/acral-lentiginous-melanoma] It occurs on non-hair-bearing surfaces of the body, which have not necessarily been exposed to sunlight.
[src:melanoma/acral-lentiginous-melanoma] Warning signs are new areas of pigmentation, or existing pigmentation that shows change.
[src:melanoma/acral-lentiginous-melanoma] If caught early, ALM has a similar cure rate as the other types of superficial spreading melanoma.
[src:melanoma/acral-lentiginous-melanoma] Acral lentiginous melanoma is a result of malignant melanocytes at the membrane of the skin (outer layers).
[src:melanoma/acral-lentiginous-melanoma] The pathogenesis of ALM remains unclear, however injury or mechanical stress might play a role in its development.
[src:melanoma/acral-lentiginous-melanoma] Unlike cutaneous melanoma, it is not caused by sunlight or UV radiation.
[src:melanoma/acral-lentiginous-melanoma] Although the ideal method of diagnosis of melanoma is complete excisional biopsy, alternative methods may be required based on the location of the melanoma.
[src:melanoma/acral-lentiginous-melanoma] Dermatoscopy of acral pigmented lesions is very difficult but can be accomplished with diligent focus.
[src:melanoma/acral-lentiginous-melanoma] Initial confirmation of the suspicion can be done with a small wedge biopsy or small punch biopsy.
[src:melanoma/acral-lentiginous-melanoma] Thin deep wedge biopsies can heal very well on acral skin, and small punch biopsies may provide enough information to suggest if a lesion is cancerous.
[src:melanoma/acral-lentiginous-melanoma] Once this confirmatory biopsy is done, a second complete excisional skin biopsy can be performed with a narrow surgical margin (1 mm).
[src:melanoma/acral-lentiginous-melanoma] This second biopsy will determine the depth and invasiveness of the melanoma, and will help to guide further treatment if necessary.
[src:melanoma/acral-lentiginous-melanoma] In order to establish the Breslow's depth of the lesion, the most raised section of the pigmented area should be sampled.
[src:melanoma/acral-lentiginous-melanoma] If the melanoma involves the nail fold or the nail bed, complete excision of the nail unit might be required for accurate sampling.
[src:melanoma/acral-lentiginous-melanoma] In the event that the melanoma spreads to other sites such as the lymph nodes, another biopsy called the Sentinel lymph node biopsy may provide more information in terms of outcomes.
[src:melanoma/acral-lentiginous-melanoma] More extensive melanomas may require wider excision (margins of 0.5 cm or more), digital amputation, lymphangiogram with lymph node dissection, or chemotherapy.
[src:melanoma/acral-lentiginous-melanoma] The main characteristic of acral lentiginous melanoma is continuous proliferation of atypical melanocytes at the dermoepidermal junction.
[src:melanoma/acral-lentiginous-melanoma] Other histological signs of acral lentiginous melanoma include dermal invasion and desmoplasia.
[src:melanoma/acral-lentiginous-melanoma] This invasion usually occurs many years after the initial lesion first appears.
[src:melanoma/acral-lentiginous-melanoma] According to Scolyer *et al.*, ALM "is usually characterized in its earliest recognisable form as single atypical melanocytes scattered along the junctional epidermal layer".
[src:melanoma/acral-lentiginous-melanoma] Other benign skin lesions that may mimic acral lentiginous melanoma include: Lentigo (sun spots), Acral Nevi (moles), or Onychomycosis (fungal infection of the nail).
[src:melanoma/acral-lentiginous-melanoma] These skin lesions can appear as dark brown spots, like ALM, but can be distinguished on close examination or dermatoscopy.
[src:melanoma/acral-lentiginous-melanoma] Other types of skin cancers like squamous cell carcinoma can also present similarly to ALM.
[src:melanoma/acral-lentiginous-melanoma] Since acral lentiginous melanoma is not linked to sun or UV exposure and the cause is not well-understood, there are no specific preventative measures.
[src:melanoma/acral-lentiginous-melanoma] However, Patient education can be geared towards populations in which ALM is more common to increase awareness of the warning signs of ALM and other melanomas to help with earlier detection.
[src:melanoma/acral-lentiginous-melanoma] Early detection is one of the most important factors in disease-specific survival.
[src:melanoma/acral-lentiginous-melanoma] The mainstay of treatment of acral lentiginous melanoma is wide local excision.
[src:melanoma/acral-lentiginous-melanoma] If metastatic, biologic immunotherapy agents like ipilimumab, pembrolizumab, and nivolumab; BRAF inhibitors, such as vemurafenib and dabrafenib; or a MEK inhibitor trametinib may be used.
[src:melanoma/acral-lentiginous-melanoma] When arising in the nailbed of a digit, the evidence suggests that digit-sparing surgery (wide excision and grafting) has similar outcomes to amputation, therefore, to preserve function and aesthetics it is recommended that clinicians default to digit-sparing surgery.
[src:melanoma/acral-lentiginous-melanoma] Secondary amputation may be considered if the surgery margins are not clear of cancerous cells, or if patients develop a recurrence of the melanoma.
[src:melanoma/acral-lentiginous-melanoma] The prognosis of acral lentiginous melanoma is based on multiple factors including sex, age, race, Breslow depth, staging, and sentinel lymph node positivity.
[src:melanoma/acral-lentiginous-melanoma] Out of these factors, it is believed that sentinel lymph node positivity provides the strongest prediction of cancer recurrence and death.
[src:melanoma/acral-lentiginous-melanoma] When compared to cutaneous malignant melanoma (CMM), ALM has a poorer prognosis in terms of survival rates.
[src:melanoma/acral-lentiginous-melanoma] This poorer prognosis is thought to be related to the fact that ALM is usually diagnosed at a later stage than other skin cancers; which may be due to ALM occurring on areas of the body that are harder to notice, especially in the elderly population.
[src:melanoma/acral-lentiginous-melanoma] The absolute incidence of ALM is the same for people of all skin colors, and has not changed significantly for decades.
[src:melanoma/acral-lentiginous-melanoma] However, because rates of other melanomas are low in non-white populations, ALM is the most common form of melanoma diagnosed amongst Asian and sub-Saharan African ethnic groups.
[src:melanoma/acral-lentiginous-melanoma] The average age at diagnosis is between sixty and seventy years.
[src:melanoma/acral-lentiginous-melanoma] Males and females are affected equally, but females tend to be diagnosed at earlier stages.
[src:melanoma/acral-lentiginous-melanoma] Jamaican musician Bob Marley died of the condition in 1981, at age 36.
[src:melanoma/acral-nevus] An **acral nevus** is a cutaneous condition of the palms, soles, fingers, or toes (peripheral body parts), characterized by a skin lesion that is usually macular or only slightly elevated, and may display a uniform brown or dark brown color, often with linear striations.
[src:melanoma/acral-nevus] Acral nevi may occur in all ethnic groups, but are more common in dark-skinned people.
[src:melanoma/acral-nevus] The acral nevus is a benign skin lesion that can occur at any age, but is generally noticed between 10 and 30 years of age.
[src:melanoma/acral-nevus] Both children and adults may be observed with this skin lesion.
[src:melanoma/acral-nevus] The prevalence of acral nevi increases directly with degree of skin pigmentation.
[src:melanoma/acral-nevus] In a study, palmar or plantar nevi were detected in 42.0% of black (50 of 119) vs 23.0% of whites (79 of 343).
[src:melanoma/acral-nevus] Palmar or plantar nevi of 6 mm diameter or larger were detected in 3.4% of blacks (4 of 119) vs 0.6% of whites.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] These growths are more common in fair-skinned people and those who are frequently in the sun.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] They are believed to form when skin gets damaged by UV radiation from the sun or indoor tanning beds, usually over the course of decades.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Given their pre-cancerous nature, if left untreated, they may turn into a type of skin cancer called squamous cell carcinoma.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Untreated lesions have up to a 20% risk of progression to squamous cell carcinoma, so treatment by a dermatologist is recommended.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Actinic keratoses characteristically appear as thick, scaly, or crusty areas that often feel dry or rough.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Size commonly ranges between 2 and 6 millimeters, but they can grow to be several centimeters in diameter.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Actinic keratoses are often felt before they are seen, and the texture is sometimes compared to sandpaper.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] They may be dark, light, tan, pink, red, a combination of all these, or have the same color as the surrounding skin.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Given the causal relationship between sun exposure and actinic keratosis growth, they often appear on a background of sun-damaged skin and in areas that are commonly sun-exposed, such as the face, ears, neck, scalp, chest, backs of hands, forearms, or lips.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Because sun exposure is rarely limited to a small area, most people who have an actinic keratosis have more than one.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Multiple treatment options for actinic keratosis are available.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Photodynamic therapy (PDT) is one option for the treatment of numerous actinic keratosis lesions in a region of the skin, termed field cancerization.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] It involves the application of a photosensitizer to the skin followed by illumination with a strong light source.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Topical creams, such as 5-fluorouracil or imiquimod, may require daily application to affected skin areas over a typical time course of weeks.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Cryotherapy is frequently used for few and well-defined lesions, but undesired skin lightening, or hypopigmentation, may occur at the treatment site.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] By following up with a dermatologist, actinic keratoses can be treated before they progress to skin cancer.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] If cancer does develop from an actinic keratosis lesion, it can be caught early with close monitoring, at a time when treatment is likely to have a high cure rate.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Actinic keratoses (AKs) most commonly present as a white, scaly plaque of variable thickness with surrounding redness; they have a sandpaper-like texture when felt with a gloved hand.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Skin nearby the lesion often shows evidence of solar damage characterized by pigmentary alterations, being yellow or pale in color with areas of hyperpigmentation; deep wrinkles, coarse texture, purpura and ecchymoses, dry skin, and scattered telangiectasias are also characteristic.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Photoaging leads to an accumulation of oncogenic changes, resulting in a proliferation of mutated keratinocytes that can manifest as actinic keratoses or other neoplastic growths.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] The lesions are usually asymptomatic, but can be tender, itch, bleed, or produce a stinging or burning sensation.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Actinic keratoses are typically graded in accordance with their clinical presentation: Grade I (easily visible, slightly palpable), Grade II (easily visible, palpable), and Grade III (frankly visible and hyperkeratotic).
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] The presence of ulceration, nodularity, or bleeding should raise concern for malignancy.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Specifically, clinical findings suggesting an increased risk of progression to squamous cell carcinoma can be recognized as "IDRBEU": I (induration/inflammation), D (diameter > 1 cm), R (rapid enlargement), B (bleeding), E (erythema), and U (ulceration).
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Actinic keratoses are usually diagnosed clinically, but because they are difficult to clinically differentiate from squamous cell carcinoma, any concerning features warrant biopsy for diagnostic confirmation.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] The most important cause of actinic keratosis formation is solar radiation, through a variety of mechanisms.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Mutation of the p53 tumor suppressor gene, induced by UV radiation, has been identified as a crucial step in actinic keratosis formation.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] This tumor suppressor gene, located on chromosome 17p132, allows for cell cycle arrest when DNA or RNA is damaged.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Dysregulation of the p53 pathway can thus result in unchecked replication of dysplastic keratinocytes, thereby serving as a source of neoplastic growth and the development of actinic keratosis, as well as possible progression from actinic keratosis to skin cancer.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Other molecular markers that have been associated with the development of actinic keratosis include the expression of p16ink4, p14, the CD95 ligand, TNF-related apoptosis-inducing ligand (TRAIL) and TRAIL receptors, and loss of heterozygosity.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Evidence also suggests that the human papillomavirus (HPV) plays a role in the development of actinic keratoses.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] The HPV virus has been detected in actinic keratoses, with measurable HPV viral loads (one HPV-DNA copy per less than 50 cells) measured in 40% of actinic keratoses.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Similar to UV radiation, higher levels of HPV found in actinic keratoses reflect enhanced viral DNA replication.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] This is suspected to be related to the abnormal keratinocyte proliferation and differentiation in actinic keratoses, which facilitate an environment for HPV replication.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] This in turn may further stimulate the abnormal proliferation that contributes to the development of actinic keratoses and carcinogenesis.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] It is thought that ultraviolet (UV) radiation induces mutations in the keratinocytes of the epidermis, promoting the survival and proliferation of these atypical cells.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Both UV-A and UV-B radiation have been implicated as causes of actinic keratoses.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] UV-A radiation (wavelength 320–400 nm) reaches more deeply into the skin and can lead to the generation of reactive oxygen species, which in turn can damage cell membranes, signaling proteins, and nucleic acids.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] UV-B radiation (wavelength 290–320 nm) causes thymidine dimer formation in DNA and RNA, leading to significant cellular mutations.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] In particular, mutations in the p53 tumor suppressor gene have been found in 30–50% of actinic keratosis lesion skin samples.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] UV radiation has also been shown to cause elevated inflammatory markers such as arachidonic acid, as well as other molecules associated with inflammation.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Eventually, over time these changes lead to the formation of actinic keratoses.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Melanin is a pigment in the epidermis that functions to protect keratinocytes from the damage caused by UV radiation; it is found in higher concentrations in the epidermis of darker-skinned individuals, affording them protection against the development of actinic keratoses.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Fair-skinned individuals have a significantly increased risk of developing actinic keratoses when compared to olive-skinned individuals (odds ratios of 14.1 and 6.5, respectively), and actinic keratoses are uncommon in dark-skinned people of African descent.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Physicians usually diagnose actinic keratosis by doing a thorough physical examination, through a combination of visual observation and touch.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] However a biopsy may be necessary when the keratosis is large in diameter, thick, or bleeding, in order to make sure that the lesion is not a skin cancer.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Actinic keratosis may progress to invasive squamous cell carcinoma (SCC) but both diseases can present similarly upon physical exam and can be difficult to distinguish clinically.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Histological examination of the lesion from a biopsy or excision may be necessary to definitively distinguish actinic keratosis from in situ or invasive SCC.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] A lesion biopsy is performed if the diagnosis remains uncertain after a clinical physical exam, or if there is suspicion that the actinic keratosis might have progressed to squamous cell carcinoma.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] The most common tissue sampling techniques include shave or punch biopsy.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] When only a portion of the lesion can be removed due to its size or location, the biopsy should sample tissue from the thickest area of the lesion, as SCCs are most likely to be detected in that area.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] If a shave biopsy is performed, it should extend through to the level of the dermis in order to provide sufficient tissue for diagnosis; ideally, it would extend to the mid-reticular dermis.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Punch biopsy usually extends to the subcutaneous fat when the entire length of the punch blade is utilized.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] On histologic examination, actinic keratoses usually show a collection of atypical keratinocytes with hyperpigmented or pleomorphic nuclei, extending to the basal layer of the epidermis.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] A "flag sign" is often described, referring to alternating areas of orthokeratosis and parakeratosis.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Epidermal thickening and surrounding areas of sun-damaged skin are often seen.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] The normal ordered maturation of the keratinocytes is disordered to varying degrees: there may be widening of the intracellular spaces, cytologic atypia such as abnormally large nuclei, and a mild chronic inflammatory infiltrate.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Specific findings depend on the clinical variant and particular lesion characteristics.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Dermoscopy is a noninvasive technique utilizing a handheld magnifying device coupled with a transilluminating lift.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] It is often used in the evaluation of cutaneous lesions but lacks the definitive diagnostic ability of biopsy-based tissue diagnosis.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Histopathologic exam remains the gold standard.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Polarized contact dermoscopy of actinic keratoses occasionally reveals a "rosette sign," described as four white points arranged in a clover pattern, often localized to within a follicular opening.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Ultraviolet radiation is believed to contribute to the development of actinic keratoses by inducing mutations in epidermal keratinocytes, leading to proliferation of atypical cells.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] There are a variety of treatment options for actinic keratosis depending on the patient and the clinical characteristics of the lesion.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Actinic keratoses show a wide range of features, which guide decision-making in choosing treatment.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] As there are multiple effective treatments, patient preference and lifestyle are also factors that physicians consider when determining the management plan for actinic keratosis.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Regular follow-up is advisable after any treatment to make sure no new lesions have developed and that old ones are not progressing.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Adding topical treatment after a procedure may improve outcomes.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Topical medications are often recommended for areas where multiple or ill-defined actinic keratoses are present, as the medication can easily be used to treat a relatively large area.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Topical fluorouracil (5-FU) destroys actinic keratoses by blocking methylation of thymidylate synthetase, thereby interrupting DNA and RNA synthesis.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] This in turn prevents the proliferation of dysplastic cells in AK.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Topical 5-FU is the most utilized treatment for AK, and often results in effective removal of the lesion.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Overall, there is a 50% efficacy rate resulting in 100% clearance of actinic keratoses treated with topical 5-FU.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] 5-FU may be up to 90% effective in treating non-hyperkeratotic lesions.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] While topical 5-FU is a widely used and cost-effective treatment for actinic keratoses and is generally well tolerated, its potential side-effects can include: pain, crusting, redness, and local swelling.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] These adverse effects can be mitigated or minimized by reducing the frequency of application or taking breaks between uses.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Calcipotriol combined with 5-fluorouracil has been found to be an effective treatment.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Imiquimod is a topical immune-enhancing agent licensed for the treatment of genital warts.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Imiquimod stimulates the immune system through the release and up-regulation of cytokines.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Treatment with Imiquimod cream applied 2–3 times per week for 12 to 16 weeks was found to result in complete resolution of actinic keratoses in 50% of people, compared to 5% of controls.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] The Imiquimod 3.75% cream has been validated in a treatment regimen consisting of daily application to entire face and scalp for two 2-week treatment cycles, with a complete clearance rate of 36%.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] However, it is ultimately difficult to compare the efficacy of the different strength creams directly, as study data varies in methodology (e.g. duration and frequency of treatment, and amount of skin surface area covered).
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Ingenol mebutate is a treatment for actinic keratosis used in Europe and the United States.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] It works in two ways, first by disrupting cell membranes and mitochondria resulting cell death, and then by inducing antibody-dependent cellular cytotoxicity to eliminate remaining tumor cells.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Treatment with the 0.015% gel was found to completely clear 57% of AK, while the 0.05% gel had a 34% clearance rate.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Advantages of ingenol mebutate treatment include the short duration of therapy and a low recurrence rate.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Ingenol mebutate has been withdrawn from the market worldwide since 2020 following safety concerns regarding an increased risk of skin cancer (squamous cell carcinoma) compared to other treatment options.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Treatment of facial actinic keratosis with diclofenac gel led to complete lesion resolution in 40% of cases.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Common side effects include dryness, itching, redness, and rash at the site of application.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Topical retinoids have been studied in the treatment of actinic keratosis with modest results, and the American Academy of Dermatology does not recommend this as first-line therapy.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Treatment with adapalene gel daily for 4 weeks, and then twice daily thereafter for a total of nine months led to a significant but modest reduction in the number of actinic keratoses compared to placebo; it demonstrated the additional advantage of improving the appearance of photodamaged skin.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Topical tretinoin is ineffective as treatment for reducing the number of actinic keratoses.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] For secondary prevention of actinic keratosis, systemic, low-dose acitretin was found to be safe, well tolerated and moderately effective in chemoprophylaxis for skin cancers in kidney transplant patients.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Acitretin is a viable treatment option for organ transplant patients according to expert opinion.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Tirbanibulin (Klisyri) was approved for medical use in the United States in December 2020, for the treatment of actinic keratosis on the face or scalp.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Liquid nitrogen (−195.8 °C) is the most commonly used destructive therapy for the treatment of actinic keratosis in the United States.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] It is a well-tolerated office procedure that does not require anesthesia.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Cryotherapy is particularly indicated for cases where there are fewer than 15 thin, well-demarcated lesions.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Caution is encouraged for thicker, more hyperkeratotic lesions, as dysplastic cells may evade treatment.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Treatment with both cryotherapy and field treatment can be considered for these more advanced lesions.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Cryotherapy is generally performed using an open-spray technique, wherein the actinic keratosis is sprayed for several seconds.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] The process can be repeated multiple times in one office visit, as tolerated.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Cure rates from 67 to 99 percent have been reported, depending on freeze time and lesion characteristics.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Disadvantages include discomfort during and after the procedure; blistering, scarring and redness; hypo- or hyperpigmentation; and destruction of healthy tissue.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Actinic keratoses are one of the most common dermatologic lesions for which photodynamic therapy, including topical methyl aminolevulinate (MAL) or 5-aminolevulinic acid (5-ALA), is indicated.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Treatment begins with preparation of the lesion, which includes scraping away scales and crusts using a dermal curette.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] A thick layer of topical MAL or 5-ALA cream is applied to the lesion and a small area surrounding the lesion, which is then covered with an occlusive dressing and left for a period of time.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] During this time the photosensitizer accumulates in the target cells within the actinic keratosis lesion.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] The dressings are then removed and the lesion is treated with light at a specified wavelength.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Multiple treatment regimens using different photosensitizers, incubation times, light sources, and pretreatment regimens have been studied and suggest that longer incubation times lead to higher rates of lesion clearance.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Photodynamic therapy is gaining in popularity.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] It has been found to have a 14% higher likelihood of achieving complete lesion clearance at 3 months compared to cryotherapy, and seems to result in superior cosmetic outcomes when compared to cryotherapy or 5-FU treatment.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Photodynamic therapy can be particularly effective in treating areas with multiple actinic keratosis lesions.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Laser therapy using carbon dioxide (CO2) or erbium:yttrium aluminum garnet (Er:YAG) lasers is a treatment approach being utilized with increased frequency, and sometimes in conjunction with computer scanning technology.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Laser therapy has not been extensively studied, but evidence suggests it may be effective in cases involving multiple actinic keratoses refractive to medical therapy, or actinic keratoses located in cosmetically sensitive locations such as the face.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] The CO2 laser has been recommended for extensive actinic cheilitis that has not responded to 5-FU.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] A chemical peel is a topically applied agent that wounds the outermost layer of the skin, promoting organized repair, exfoliation, and eventually the development of smooth and rejuvenated skin.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] A medium-depth peel may effectively treat multiple non-hyperkeratotic actinic keratoses.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] It can be achieved with 35% to 50% trichloroacetic acid (TCA) alone or at 35% in combination with Jessner's solution in a once-daily application for a minimum of 3 weeks; 70% glycolic acid (α-hydroxy acid); or solid CO2.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] When compared to treatment with 5-FU, chemical peels have demonstrated similar efficacy and increased ease of use with similar morbidity.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Chemical peels must be performed in a controlled clinic environment and are recommended only for individuals who are able to comply with follow-up precautions, including avoidance of sun exposure.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Furthermore, they should be avoided in individuals with a history of HSV infection or keloids, and in those who are immunosuppressed or who are taking photosensitizing medications.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Untreated actinic keratoses follow one of three paths: they can either persist as actinic keratoses, regress, or progress to invasive skin cancer, as actinic keratosis lesions are considered to be on the same continuum with squamous cell carcinoma (SCC).
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Actinic keratosis lesions that regress also have the potential to recur.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Given the aforementioned differering clinical outcomes, it is difficult to predict the clinical course of any given actinic keratosis.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Actinic keratosis lesions may also come and go—in a cycle of appearing on the skin, remaining for months, and then disappearing.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Often they will reappear in a few weeks or months, particularly after unprotected sun exposure.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Left untreated, there is a chance that the lesion will advance to become invasive.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Although it is difficult to predict whether an actinic keratosis will advance to become squamous cell carcinoma, it has been noted that squamous cell carcinomas originate in lesions formerly diagnosed as actinic keratoses with frequencies reported between 65 and 97%.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Actinic keratosis is very common, with an estimated 14% of dermatology visits related to actinic keratoses.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] It is seen more often in fair-skinned individuals, and rates vary with geographical location and age.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Other factors such as exposure to ultraviolet (UV) radiation, certain phenotypic features, and immunosuppression can also contribute to the development of actinic keratoses.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Men are more likely to develop actinic keratosis than women, and the risk of developing actinic keratosis lesions increases with age.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] These findings have been observed in multiple studies, with numbers from one study suggesting that approximately 5% of women ages 20–29 develop actinic keratosis compared to 68% of women ages 60–69, and 10% of men ages 20–29 develop actinic keratosis compared to 79% of men ages 60–69.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Geography seems to play a role in the sense that individuals living in locations where they are exposed to more UV radiation throughout their lifetime have a significantly higher risk of developing actinic keratosis.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Much of the literature on actinic keratosis comes from Australia, where the prevalence of actinic keratosis is estimated at 40–50% in adults over 40, as compared to the United States and Europe, where prevalence is estimated at under 11–38% in adults.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] One study found that those who immigrated to Australia after age 20 had fewer actinic keratoses than native Australians in all age groups.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Research implicating human papillomavirus (HPV) in the development of actinic keratoses suggests that HPV prevention might in turn help prevent development of actinic keratoses, as UV-induced mutations and oncogenic transformation are likely facilitated in cases of active HPV infection.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] A key component of HPV prevention includes vaccination.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] There are some data that in individuals with a history of non-melanoma skin cancer, a low-fat diet can serve as a preventative measure against future actinic keratoses.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Diagnostically, researchers are investigating the role of novel biomarkers to assist in determining which actinic keratoses are more likely to develop into cutaneous or metastatic SCC.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Upregulation of matrix metalloproteinases (MMP) is seen in many different types of cancers, and the expression and production of MMP-7 in particular has been found to be elevated in SCC specifically.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] The role of serin peptidase inhibitors (Serpins) is also being investigated.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] SerpinA1 was found to be elevated in the keratinocytes of SCC cell lines, and SerpinA1 upregulation was correlated with SCC tumor progression *in vivo*.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] In terms of treatment, a number of medications are being studied.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Resiquimod is a TLR 7/8 agonist that works similarly to imiquimod, but is 10 to 100 times more potent; when used to treat actinic keratosis lesions, complete response rates have range from 40 to 74%.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Afamelanotide is a drug that induces the production of melanin by melanocytes to act as a protective factor against UVB radiation.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] It is being studied to determine its efficacy in preventing actinic keratoses in organ transplant patients who are on immunosuppressive therapy.
[src:melanoma/actinic-keratosis] Epidermal growth factor receptor (EGFR) inhibitors such as gefitinib, and anti-EGFR antibodies such as cetuximab are used in the treatment of various types of cancers, and are being investigated for potential use in the treatment and prevention of actinic keratoses.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] In females, melanomas most commonly occur on the legs; while in males, on the back.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Melanoma is frequently referred to as **malignant melanoma**.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] However, the medical community stresses that there is no such thing as a 'benign melanoma' and recommends that the term 'malignant melanoma' should be avoided as it is redundant.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] About 30% of melanomas develop from moles.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Changes in a mole that can indicate melanoma include increase—especially rapid increase—in size, irregular edges, change in color, itchiness, or skin breakdown.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] The primary cause of melanoma is ultraviolet light (UV) exposure in those with low levels of the skin pigment melanin.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] The UV light may be from the sun or other sources, such as tanning devices.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Those with many moles, a history of affected family members, and poor immune function are at greater risk.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] A number of rare genetic conditions, such as xeroderma pigmentosum, also increase the risk.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Diagnosis is by biopsy and analysis of any skin lesion that has signs of being potentially cancerous.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Avoiding UV light and using sunscreen in UV-bright sun conditions may prevent melanoma.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Treatment typically is removal by surgery of the melanoma and the potentially affected adjacent tissue bordering the melanoma.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] In those with slightly larger cancers, nearby lymph nodes may be tested for spread (metastasis).
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Most people are cured if metastasis has not occurred.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] For those in whom melanoma has spread, immunotherapy, biologic therapy, radiation therapy, or chemotherapy may improve survival.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] With treatment, the five-year survival rates in the United States are 100% among those with localized disease, 76% when the disease has spread to lymph nodes, and 35% among those with distant spread.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] The likelihood that melanoma will reoccur or spread depends on its thickness, how fast the cells are dividing, and whether or not the overlying skin has broken down.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Melanoma is the most dangerous type of skin cancer.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] In 2015, 3.1 million people had active disease, which resulted in 59,800 deaths.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] The incidence of melanoma is expected to increase from 331,722 worldwide cases in 2022 to 510,000 cases in 2040.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] However mortality is decreasing as newer treatments become available.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] About 80% of all global cases occur in adults 50 years or older.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Australia and New Zealand have the highest rates of melanoma in the world.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] High rates also occur in Northern Europe and North America, while it is less common in Asia, Africa, and Latin America.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] In the United States, melanoma occurs about 1.6 times more often in men than women.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Melanoma has become more common since the 1960s in areas mostly populated by people of European descent.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Early signs of melanoma are changes to the shape or color of existing moles or, in the case of nodular melanoma, the appearance of a new lump anywhere on the skin.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] At later stages, the mole may itch, ulcerate, or bleed.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Metastatic melanoma may cause nonspecific paraneoplastic symptoms, including loss of appetite, nausea, vomiting, and fatigue.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Brain metastases are particularly common in patients with metastatic melanoma.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Other common sites of metastasis of melanoma include liver, intestines, bone, lungs and distant lymph nodes.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Melanomas are typically caused by DNA damage resulting from exposure to UV light from the sun.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Melanoma can also occur in skin areas with little sun exposure (i.e., mouth, soles of feet, palms of hands, genital areas).
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] People with dysplastic nevus syndrome, also known as familial atypical multiple mole melanoma, are at increased risk for the development of melanoma.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Having more than 50 moles indicates an increased risk of melanoma.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] A weakened immune system makes cancer development easier due to the body's weakened ability to fight cancer cells.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] The main risk factor for melanoma formation is exposure to UV radiation, either from sunlight or indoor tanning.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] UV radiation exposure from tanning beds increases the risk of melanoma.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] The International Agency for Research on Cancer finds that tanning beds are "carcinogenic to humans" and that people who begin using tanning devices before the age of thirty years are 75% more likely to develop melanoma.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Those who work in airplanes also appear to have an increased risk, believed to be due to greater exposure to UV.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] UVB light, emanating from the sun at wavelengths between 315 and 280 nm, is absorbed directly by DNA in skin cells, which results in a type of direct DNA damage called cyclobutane pyrimidine dimers.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Thymine, cytosine, or cytosine-thymine dimers are formed by the joining of two adjacent pyrimidine bases within a strand of DNA.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] UVA light presents at wavelengths longer than UVB (between 400 and 315 nm); and it can also be absorbed directly by DNA in skin cells, but at lower efficiencies—about 1/100 to 1/1000 of UVB.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Radiation exposure (UVA and UVB) is a major contributor to the development of melanoma.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Occasional extreme sun exposure that results in "sunburn" on areas of the human body is causally related to melanoma.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] The risk appears to be strongly influenced by socioeconomic conditions rather than indoor versus outdoor occupations; it is more common in professional and administrative workers than in unskilled workers.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Other factors are mutations in (or total loss of) tumor suppressor genes.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Possible significant elements in determining risk include the intensity and duration of sun exposure, the age at which sun exposure occurs, and the degree of skin pigmentation.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Melanoma rates tend to be highest in countries settled by migrants from Europe, which have a large amount of direct, intense sunlight to which the skin of the settlers is not adapted, most notably Australia.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Exposure during childhood is a more important risk factor than exposure in adulthood.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] This is seen in migration studies in Australia.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Incurring multiple severe sunburns increases the likelihood that future sunburns develop into melanoma due to cumulative damage.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Living close to the equator increases exposure to UV radiation.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] It is believed that 5-12% of melanoma is hereditary.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Having a family history of melanoma increases one's risk, with having a first-degree relative increasing one's risk of developing melanoma by 1.74 times.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Having a personal history of melanoma increases the risk of developing another melanoma in the future, by some estimates an 8.40 times increased risk.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Familial melanoma is more likely to present at an earlier age and more likely to present as multiple skin lesions than non-familial melanoma.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Familial melanoma is also more likely to present as thinner lesions (less depth of skin invasion.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] A number of rare mutations, which often run in families, greatly increase melanoma susceptibility.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Some rare genes have a relatively high risk of causing melanoma; some more common genes, such as a gene called *MC1R* that causes red hair, have an elevated risk.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Genetic testing can be used to search for the mutations.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Melanoma with genetic mutations in the BRAF genes V600E or V600K (proteins involved in cell growth) are more responsive to therapy with the BRAF inhibitor dabrafenib plus trametinib.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] One class of mutations affects the gene *CDKN2A*.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] An alternative reading frame mutation in this gene leads to the destabilization of p53, a transcription factor involved in apoptosis and in 50% of human cancers.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Another mutation in the same gene results in a nonfunctional inhibitor of CDK4, a cyclin-dependent kinase that promotes cell division.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Mutations that cause the skin condition xeroderma pigmentosum (XP) also increase melanoma susceptibility.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Scattered throughout the genome, these mutations reduce a cell's ability to repair DNA.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Both CDKN2A and XP mutations are highly penetrant (the chances of a carrier expressing the phenotype are high).
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Familial melanoma is genetically heterogeneous, and loci for familial melanoma appear on the chromosome arms 1p, 9p and 12q.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Multiple genetic events have been related to melanoma's pathogenesis (disease development).
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] The multiple tumor suppressor 1 (CDKN2A/MTS1) gene encodes p16INK4a – a low-molecular weight protein inhibitor of cyclin-dependent protein kinases (CDKs) – which has been localised to the p21 region of human chromosome 9.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Dysplastic nevus syndrome also known as FAMMM (familial atypical multiple mole-melanoma) is typically characterized by having 50 or more combined moles in addition to a family history of melanoma.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] It is transmitted autosomal dominantly and mostly associated with the *CDKN2A* mutations.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] People who have a CDKN2A mutation associated with FAMMM have a 38-fold increased risk of pancreatic cancer.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] People with FAMMM also have a 30% lifetime risk of developing melanoma.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] People with mutations in the *MC1R* gene are two to 2.7-3.6 times more likely to develop melanoma than those with two wild-type (typical unaffected type) copies.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Some MC1R gene variants are more common in those with red hair.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Mutation of the *MDM2* SNP309 gene is associated with increased risks for younger women.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Fair and red-haired people, persons with multiple atypical nevi or dysplastic nevi, and persons born with giant congenital melanocytic nevi are at increased risk.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Fair skin is the result of having less melanin in the skin, which means less protection from UV radiation exists.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] The earliest stage of melanoma starts when melanocytes begin out-of-control growth.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Melanocytes are found between the outer layer of the skin (the epidermis) and the next layer (the dermis).
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] This early stage of the disease is called the radial growth phase, when the tumor is less than 1 mm thick, and spreads at the level of the basal epidermis.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Because the cancer cells have not yet reached the blood vessels deeper in the skin, it is very unlikely that this early-stage melanoma will spread to other parts of the body.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] If the melanoma is detected at this stage, then it can usually be completely removed with surgery.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] When the tumor cells start to move in a different direction – vertically up into the epidermis and into the papillary dermis – cell behaviour changes dramatically.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] The next step in the evolution is the invasive radial growth phase, in which individual cells start to acquire invasive potential.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] From this point on, melanoma is capable of spreading.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] The Breslow's depth of the lesion is usually less than 1 mm (0.04 in), while the Clark level is usually 2.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] The vertical growth phase (VGP) following invasive melanoma.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] The tumor becomes able to grow into the surrounding tissue and can spread around the body through blood or lymph vessels.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] The tumor thickness is usually more than 1 mm (0.04 in), and the tumor involves the deeper parts of the dermis.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] The host elicits an immunological reaction against the tumor during the VGP, which is judged by the presence and activity of the tumor infiltrating lymphocytes (TILs).
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] These cells sometimes completely destroy the primary tumor; this is called regression, which is the latest stage of development.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] In certain cases, the primary tumor is completely destroyed and only the metastatic tumor is discovered.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] About 40% of human melanomas contain activating mutations affecting the structure of the B-Raf protein, resulting in constitutive signaling through the Raf to MAP kinase pathway.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] A cause common to most cancers is damage to DNA.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] UVA also produces reactive oxygen species and these inflict other DNA damage, primarily single-strand breaks, oxidized pyrimidines and the oxidized purine 8-oxoguanine (a mutagenic DNA change) at 1/10, 1/10, and 1/3rd the frequencies of UVA-induced thymine dimers, respectively.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] If unrepaired, cyclobutane pyrimidine dimer (CPD) photoproducts can lead to mutations by inaccurate translesion synthesis during DNA replication or repair.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] The most frequent mutations due to inaccurate synthesis past CPDs are cytosine to thymine (C>T) or CC>TT transition mutations.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] These are commonly referred to as UV fingerprint mutations, as they are the most specific mutation caused by UV, being frequently found in sun-exposed skin, but rarely found in internal organs.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Errors in DNA repair of UV photoproducts, or inaccurate synthesis past these photoproducts, can also lead to deletions, insertions, and chromosomal translocations.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] The entire genomes of 25 melanomas were sequenced.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] On average, about 80,000 mutated bases (mostly C>T transitions) and about 100 structural rearrangements were found per melanoma genome.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] This is much higher than the roughly 70 mutations across generations (parent to child).
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Among the 25 melanomas, about 6,000 protein-coding genes had missense, nonsense, or splice site mutations.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] The transcriptomes of over 100 melanomas has also been sequenced and analyzed.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Almost 70% of all human protein-coding genes are expressed in melanoma.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Most of these genes are also expressed in other normal and cancer tissues, with some 200 genes showing a more specific expression pattern in melanoma compared to other forms of cancer.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Examples of melanoma specific genes are tyrosinase, MLANA, and *PMEL*.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] UV radiation causes damage to the DNA of cells, typically thymine dimerization, which, when unrepaired, can create mutations in the cell's genes.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] This strong mutagenic factor makes cutaneous melanoma the tumor type with the highest number of mutations.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] When the cell divides, these mutations are propagated to new generations of cells.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] If the mutations occur in protooncogenes or tumor suppressor genes, the rate of mitosis in the mutation-bearing cells can become uncontrolled, leading to the formation of a tumor.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Large-scale studies, such as The Cancer Genome Atlas, have characterized recurrent somatic alterations likely driving initiation and development of cutaneous melanoma.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] The Cancer Genome Atlas study has established four subtypes: *BRAF* mutant, *RAS* mutant, *NF1* mutant, and triple wild-type.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] The most frequent mutation occurs in the 600th codon of *BRAF* (50% of cases).
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] *BRAF* is normally involved in cell growth, and this specific mutation renders the protein constitutively active and independent of normal physiological regulation, thus fostering tumor growth.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] RAS genes (NRAS, HRAS and KRAS) are also recurrently mutated (30% of TCGA cases) and mutations in the 61st or 12th codons trigger oncogenic activity.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Loss-of-function mutations often affect tumor suppressor genes such as NF1, TP53 and CDKN2A.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Other oncogenic alterations include fusions involving various kinases such as BRAF, RAF1, ALK, RET, ROS1, NTRK1., NTRK3 and MET*BRAF, RAS*, and *NF1* mutations and kinase fusions are remarkably mutually exclusive, as they occur in different subsets of patients.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Assessment of mutation status can, therefore, improve patient stratification and inform targeted therapy with specific inhibitors.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] In some cases (3–7%), mutated versions of *BRAF* and *NRAS* undergo copy-number amplification.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] The research done by Sarna's team proved that heavily pigmented melanoma cells have Young's modulus about 4.93, while in non-pigmented ones it was only 0.98.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] In another experiment they found that elasticity of melanoma cells is important for its metastasis and growth: non-pigmented tumors were bigger than pigmented and it was much easier for them to spread.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] They showed that there are both pigmented and non-pigmented cells in melanoma tumors, so that they can both be drug-resistant and metastatic.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Visually inspecting the skin lesion in question is the first step in diagnosing a suspected a melanoma.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Moles that are irregular in color or shape are suspicious for melanoma.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] To detect melanomas, it is recommended to learn to recognize them (see "ABCDE" mnemonic), to regularly examine moles for changes (shape, size, color, itching or bleeding) and to consult a qualified physician when a suspicious skin lesion appears.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] In-person inspection of suspicious skin lesions is more accurate than visual inspection of images.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] When used by trained specialists, dermoscopy is more helpful to identify malignant lesions than use of the naked eye alone.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Reflectance confocal microscopy may have better sensitivity and specificity than dermoscopy in diagnosing cutaneous melanoma but more studies are needed to confirm this result.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Many melanomas present as lesions smaller than 6 mm in diameter.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Physicians typically examine all moles, including those less than 6 mm in diameter.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Seborrheic keratosis may meet some or all of the ABCD criteria and may be sometimes mistaken for melanoma.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Doctors can generally distinguish seborrheic keratosis from melanoma upon examination or with dermatoscopy.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Total body photography, which involves photographic documentation of as much body surface as possible, is sometimes used to objectively observe the evolution of body moles over time, to potentially find moles that become suspicious.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] It is often used during follow-up for high-risk patients.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] The technique has been reported to enable early detection and provide a cost-effective approach, but its efficacy has been questioned due to its inability to detect microscopic changes.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] One method of finding lesions that are suspected melanomas is the "ugly duckling sign".
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] People's moles tend to look like one another, but when there is a mole that looks different from someone's other moles, it is more likely to be a melanoma.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] The "Little Red Riding Hood" sign suggests that individuals with fair skin and light-colored hair might have difficult-to-diagnose amelanotic melanomas.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Extra care is required when examining such individuals, as they might have multiple melanomas and severely dysplastic nevi.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Amelanotic melanomas (a rare subtype) have very little to no pigmentation and are therefore more difficult to detect.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] The acral subtype of melanoma presents in areas that do not usually get sun exposure and are difficult to see by a person (the soles of the feet, and palms of hand) making detection difficult.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Thirty to 40% of acral melanomas are amelanotic (producing little to no pigment), also making the diagnosis challenging.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Following a visual examination and a dermatoscopic exam, or other specialized tests such as confocal microscopy, a skin biopsy is done for lesions suspicious of being melanoma.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] A skin biopsy is required for definitive diagnosis of melanoma and staging the cancer.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Elliptical excisional biopsies may remove the tumor, followed by histological analysis and Breslow scoring.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Incisional biopsies such as punch biopsies are usually contraindicated in suspected melanomas, because of the possibility of sampling error or local implantation causing misestimation of tumour thickness.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] However, fears that such biopsies may increase the risk of metastatic disease seem unfounded.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Melanoma is a type of neuroectodermal neoplasm.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] A melanoma *in situ* has not invaded beyond the basement membrane, whereas an *invasive melanoma* has spread beyond it.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Some histopathological types of melanoma are inherently invasive, including nodular melanoma and lentigo maligna melanoma, where the *in situ* counterpart to lentigo maligna melanoma is lentigo maligna.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Lentigo maligna is sometimes classified as a very early melanoma, and sometimes a precursor to melanoma.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Superficial spreading melanomas and acral lentiginous melanomas can be either *in situ* or invasive, but acral lentiginous melanomas are almost always invasive.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Melanomas are staged based on the depth of invasion in various layers of the skin, the presence of ulceration, spread to local lymph nodes or spread to distant lymph nodes and organs (metastasis).
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Metastatic melanomas can be detected by CT scans, MRIs, and PET/CTs, or ultrasound.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] PET/CT to assess for metastasis is generally recommended for people with stage IIB or greater melanoma.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] If a person has an ulcerated lesion, or if the depth of tumor invasion is greater than 0.8 mm, then a sentinel lymph node biopsy is recommended.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] LDH levels may sometimes be elevated in metastatic melanoma, but this is not required for the diagnosis nor staging.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Older systems include "Clark level" and "Breslow's depth", quantifying microscopic depth of tumor invasion.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] It is common for patients diagnosed with melanoma to have chest X-rays, and in some cases CT, MRI, and/or PET scans.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] A diagnosis of melanoma is supported by the presence of the S-100 protein marker.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] HMB-45 is a monoclonal antibody that reacts against an antigen present in melanocytic tumors such as melanomas.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] It is used in anatomic pathology as a marker for such tumors.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] The antibody was generated against an extract of melanoma.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] It reacts positively against melanocytic tumors but not other tumors, thus demonstrating specificity and sensitivity.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] The antibody also reacts positively against junctional nevus cells but not intradermal nevi, and against fetal melanocytes but not normal adult melanocytes.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] HMB-45 is nonreactive with almost all non-melanoma human malignancies, except rare tumors showing evidence of melanogenesis (e.g., pigmented schwannoma, clear cell sarcoma) or tumors associated with tuberous sclerosis complex (angiomyolipoma and lymphangiomyoma).
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] There is no evidence to support or refute adult population screening for melanoma.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Minimizing exposure to sources of ultraviolet radiation (the sun and sunbeds) and other sun protection measures such as wearing sun protective clothing (long-sleeved shirts, long trousers, and broad-brimmed hats) can offer protection.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Using artificial light for tanning was once believed to help prevent skin cancers, but it can lead to an increased incidence of melanomas.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] UV nail lamps, which are used in nail salons to dry nail polish, are another widespread source of UV radiation that could be avoided.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Although the risk of developing skin cancer through UV nail lamp use is low, it is still recommended to wear fingerless gloves and/or apply SPF 30 or greater sunscreen to the hands before using a UV nail lamp.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Exposure to sunlight can be intermittent instead of all at one time.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Sunscreen appears to be effective in preventing melanoma.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] In the past, use of sunscreens with a sun protection factor (SPF) rating of 50 or higher on exposed areas were recommended; as older sunscreens more effectively blocked UVA with higher SPF.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Currently, newer sunscreen ingredients (avobenzone, zinc oxide, and titanium dioxide) effectively block both UVA and UVB even at lower SPFs.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Sunscreen also protects against squamous cell carcinoma, another skin cancer.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Concerns have been raised that sunscreen might create a false sense of security against sun damage.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] A 2005 review found tentative evidence that statin and fibrate medication may decrease the risk of melanoma.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] A 2006 review however did not support any benefit.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Confirmation of the clinical diagnosis is done with a skin biopsy.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] This is usually followed up with a wider excision of the scar or tumor.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Depending on the stage, a sentinel lymph node biopsy may be performed.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Controversy exists around benefit for sentinel lymph node biopsy; with unclear evidence of benefit as of 2015.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Excisional biopsies may remove the tumor, but further surgery is often necessary to make sure all of the tumor is removed and reduce the risk of recurrence.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Complete surgical excision with adequate surgical margins is standard.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Often this is done by a wide local excision (WLE) with 5 mm to 2 cm margins.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Melanoma-in-situ and lentigo malignas are treated with narrower surgical margins, usually 0.2 to 5 mm.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] A wide-local excision usually removes 5 mm to 2 cm around the tumor, with the margins determined by the Breslow Depth (2 cm margins are removed for a Breslow tumor Depth greater than 2 mm).
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Mohs surgery, or the double-bladed technique with margin control is sometimes used.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] The sample is inspected histologically to make sure no tumor cells involve the cut margins, indicating an inadequate tumor of removal.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] The wide excision aims to reduce the rate of tumor recurrence at the site of the original lesion.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] A 2009 meta-analysis of randomized controlled trials found a small difference in survival rates favoring wide excision of primary cutaneous melanomas, but these results were not statistically significant.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Mohs surgery has been reported with cure rate as low as 77% and as high as 98.0% for melanoma-in-situ.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] CCPDMA and the "double scalpel" peripheral margin controlled surgery is equivalent to Mohs surgery in removal of melanoma in-situ.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Melanomas that spread usually do so to the lymph nodes in the area of the tumor before spreading elsewhere.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Attempts to improve survival by removing lymph nodes surgically (lymph node dissection) were associated with many complications, but no overall survival benefit.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Sentinel lymph node biopsy may indicate if cancer has spread to local lymph nodes and guide treatment decisions.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Neither sentinel lymph node biopsy nor other diagnostic tests should be performed to evaluate early, thin melanoma, including melanoma in situ, T1a melanoma, or T1b melanoma ≤ 0.5mm.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] People with these conditions are unlikely to have the cancer spread to their lymph nodes or anywhere else and have a 5-year survival rate of 97%.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Sentinel lymph node biopsy is indicated for ulcerated melanomas or melanomas of greater than 0.8 mm thickness.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] A process called lymphoscintigraphy is performed in which a radioactive tracer is injected at the tumor site to localize the sentinel node.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Further precision is provided using a blue tracer dye, and surgery is performed to biopsy the node.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Routine hematoxylin and eosin and immunoperoxidase staining will be adequate to rule out node involvement.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] If a lymph node is positive, depending on the extent of lymph node spread, a radical lymph node dissection may be performed in which affected lymph nodes are surgically removed.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Lymph node dissection is not associated with a survival benefit in those with melanoma and is no longer recommended.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Adjuvant treatment after surgery may reduce the risk of recurrence, especially in high-risk melanomas.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] The most common adjuvant treatment is immune checkpoint inhibitor treatment for up to a year post-surgery.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] In the early 2000s, a relatively common strategy was to treat patients with a high risk of recurrence with up to a year of high-dose interferon treatment.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] A 2013 meta-analysis suggested that the addition of interferon alpha increased disease-free and overall survival for people with AJCC TNM stage II-III cutaneous melanoma.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] A 2011 meta-analysis showed that interferon could lengthen the time before a melanoma comes back but increased survival by only 3% at 5 years.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] The unpleasant side effects also greatly decrease the quality of life.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Interferon is no longer routinely used in the treatment of melanoma outside of clinical trials.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Chemotherapy drugs such as dacarbazine have been commonly used for metastatic melanoma since the 1970s; however, their efficacy in terms of survival has never been proven in an RCT.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Since the approval of immune checkpoint inhibitors, dacarbazine and its oral counterpart, temozolomide, constitute potential treatment options in later lines of therapy.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Multiple drugs are available to patients to decrease the size of the tumor.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] By lessening the size of the tumor, some symptoms can be relieved; however, this does not necessarily lead to remission.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Some of these drugs are dacarbazine, temozolomide, and fotemustine.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Combinations of drugs are also used and, in some cases, present higher remission rates.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Although combinations of drugs increase remission rates, the survival rate does not show an increase.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] In people with locally advanced cutaneous malignancies and sarcoma, isolated limb infusion (ILI) has been found to be a minimally invasive and well-tolerated procedure for delivering regional chemotherapy.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Melanoma cells have mutations that allow them to survive and grow indefinitely in the body.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Small-molecule targeted therapies work by blocking the genes involved in pathways for tumor proliferation and survival.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] The main treatments are BRAF, C-Kit and NRAS inhibitors.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] These inhibitors work to inhibit the downstream pathways involved in cell proliferation and tumour development due to specific gene mutations.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] People can be treated with small-molecule targeted inhibitors if they are positive for the specific mutation.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] BRAF inhibitors, such as vemurafenib and dabrafenib and a MEK inhibitor trametinib are the most effective, approved treatments for BRAF positive melanoma.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Melanoma tumors can develop resistance during therapy which can make therapy no longer effective, but combining the use of BRAF and MEK inhibitors may create a fast and lasting melanoma therapy response.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Several treatments improve survival over traditional chemotherapy.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Biochemotherapy (chemotherapy with cytokines IL-2 and IFN-α) combined with BRAF inhibitors improved survival for people with BRAF-positive melanoma.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Biochemotherapy alone did not improve overall survival and had higher toxicity than chemotherapy.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Combining multiple chemotherapy agents (polychemotherapy) did not improve survival over monochemotherapy.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Targeted therapies result in relatively short progression-free survival (PFS) times.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] The therapy combination of dabrafenib and trametinib has a 3-year PFS of 23% and a 5-year PFS of 13%.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Lifileucel (Amtagvi) is a tumor-derived autologous T-cell immunotherapy that was approved for medical use in the United States in February 2024.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Immunotherapy is aimed at stimulating the person's immune system against the tumor to enhance the body's ability to recognize and kill cancer cells.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] The current approach to treating melanoma with immunotherapy includes three broad categories of treatments, including cytokines, immune checkpoint inhibitors, and adoptive cell transfer.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] These treatment options are most often used in people with metastatic melanoma and significantly improve overall survival.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Cytokine therapies used for melanoma include IFN-a and IL-2.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] IL-2 (Proleukin) was the first new therapy approved (1990 EU, 1992 US) for the treatment of metastatic melanoma in 20 years.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] IL-2 may offer the possibility of a complete and long-lasting remission in this disease in a small percentage of people with melanoma.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Intralesional IL-2 for in-transit metastases has a high complete response rate ranging from 40 to 100%.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Similarly, IFN-α has shown only modest survival benefits and high toxicity, limiting its use as a stand-alone therapy.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Immune check point inhibitors include anti-CTLA-4 monoclonal antibodies (ipilimumab and tremelimumab), toll-like receptor (TLR) agonists, CD40 agonists, anti-PD-1 (pembrolizumab, pidilizumab, and nivolumab) and PD-L1 antibodies.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Evidence suggests that anti-PD-1 antibodies are more effective than anti-CTLA4 antibodies with less systemic toxicity.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] The five-year progression-free survival for immunotherapy with pembrolizumab is 21%.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Nivolumab or pembrolizumab was associated with increased recurrence free survival at 12 months of treatment.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] These medications block PD-1 to inhibit T-cell inactivation, this leads to more T-cell proliferation and activity against melanoma cells.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Either medication is indicated in Stage IIB-C disease (or observation after resection without using medication is also a treatment option).
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] For stage IIIA-D disease, resection of tumor may be followed by 12 months of treatment with nivolumab or pembrolizumab or dabrafenib (BRAF inhibitor) plus trametinib (MEK inhibitor)in BRAF gene positive disease.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Observation after resection (without using immunotherapy) is also an option, but immunotherapy after resection is associated with an improved cancer-free survival rate at 5 years.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] In those with stage III or IV disease that cannot be surgically removed, dual checkpoint blockade by combining nivolumab and ipilimumab (anti-CTLA4 inhibitor) followed by maintenance nivolumab is associated with increased survival and has a lower mortality than using either agent alone.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] A therapeutic approach that includes the combination of different therapies improves overall survival and progression-free survival compared to treatment with the separate immunotherapy drugs alone.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] However, combination therapy also has a higher risk of immune-related adverse reactions (due to hyperactivity of the immune system).
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Ongoing research is looking at treatment by adoptive cell transfer.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Adoptive cell transfer refers to the application of pre-stimulated, modified T cells or dendritic cells and is presently used to minimize complications from graft-versus-host disease.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] The combination nivolumab/relatlimab (Opdualag) was approved for medical use in the United States in March 2022.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Standard excision is still being done by most surgeons.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Unfortunately, the recurrence rate is exceedingly high (up to 50%).
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] This is due to the ill-defined visible surgical margin and the facial location of the lesions (often forcing the surgeon to use a narrow surgical margin).
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] The narrow surgical margin used, combined with the limitation of the standard "bread-loafing" technique of fixed tissue histology, results in a high "false negative" error rate and frequent recurrences.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Margin control (peripheral margins) is necessary to eliminate the false-negative errors.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] If bread loafing is used, distances from sections should approach 0.1 mm to assure that the method approaches complete margin control.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] A meta-analysis of the literature in 2014 found no randomized controlled trials of surgical interventions to treat lentigo maligna or melanoma in situ, even though surgery is the most widely used treatment.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Mohs surgery has been done with cure rate reported to be as low as 77%, and as high as 95% by another author.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] The "double scalpel" peripheral margin controlled excision method approximates the Mohs method in margin control, but requires a pathologist intimately familiar with the complexity of managing the vertical margin on the thin peripheral sections and staining methods.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Some melanocytic nevi, and melanoma-in-situ (lentigo maligna) have resolved with an experimental treatment, imiquimod (Aldara) topical cream, an immune enhancing agent.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Some derma-surgeons are combining the two methods: surgically excising the cancer and then treating the area with Aldara cream postoperatively for three months.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] While some studies have suggested the adjuvant use of topical tazarotene, the current evidence is insufficient to recommend it and suggests that it increases topical inflammation, leading to lower patient compliance.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Radiation therapy is often used after surgical resection for patients with locally or regionally advanced melanoma or for patients with unresectable distant metastases.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Kilovoltage x-ray beams are often used for these treatments and have the property that the maximum radiation dose occurs close to the skin surface.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] It may reduce the rate of local recurrence but does not prolong survival.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Radioimmunotherapy of metastatic melanoma is currently under investigation.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p01] Radiotherapy has a role in the palliation of metastatic melanoma.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] Certain types of melanoma have worse prognoses, but this is explained by their thickness.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] Less invasive melanomas, even with lymph node metastases, carry a better prognosis than deep melanomas without regional metastasis at the time of staging.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] Local recurrences tend to behave similarly to a primary unless they are at the site of a wide local excision (as opposed to a staged excision or punch/shave excision) since these recurrences tend to indicate lymphatic invasion.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] When melanomas have spread to the lymph nodes, one of the most important factors is the number of nodes with malignancy.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] The extent of malignancy within a node is also important; micrometastases, in which malignancy is only microscopic, have a more favorable prognosis than macrometastases.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] In some cases, micrometastases may only be detected by special staining, and if malignancy is only detectable by polymerase chain reaction (PCR), the prognosis is better.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] Macro-metastases in which malignancy is clinically apparent (in some cases, cancer completely replaces a node) have a far worse prognosis, and if nodes are matted or if there is extracapsular extension, the prognosis is worse still.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] In addition to these variables, expression levels and copy number variations of several relevant genes may be used to support assessment of melanoma prognosis.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] Stage IV melanoma, in which it has metastasized, is the most deadly skin malignancy: five-year survival in the United States was 34.6% for people diagnosed between 2015 and 2021.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] Metastases to the skin and lungs have a better prognosis.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] Metastases to the brain, bone, and liver are associated with a worse prognosis.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] Survival is better with metastasis in which the location of the primary tumor is unknown.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] Survival rates have rapidly increased in the decade leading up to 2025.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] There is not enough definitive evidence to adequately stage, and thus give a prognosis for, ocular melanoma and melanoma of soft parts, or mucosal melanoma (e.g., rectal melanoma), although these tend to metastasize more easily.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] Even though regression may increase survival, when a melanoma has regressed, it is impossible to know its original size, and thus the original tumor is often worse than a pathology report might indicate.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] About 200 genes are prognostic in melanoma, with both unfavorable genes where high expression is correlated to poor survival and favorable genes where high expression is associated with longer survival times.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] Examples of unfavorable genes are MCM6 and TIMELESS; an example of a favorable gene is WIPI1.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] An increased neutrophil-to-lymphocyte ratio is associated with worse outcomes.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] Globally, in 2012, melanoma occurred in 232,000 people and resulted in 55,000 deaths.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] It has become more common in the last 20 years in areas that are mostly Caucasian.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] Australia has a very high and increasing rate of melanoma.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] In 2012, deaths from melanoma occurred in 7.3–9.8 per 100,000 population.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] In Australia, melanoma is the third most common cancer in both sexes; indeed, its incidence is higher than for lung cancer, although the latter accounts for more deaths.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] It is estimated that in 2012, more than 12,000 Australians were diagnosed with melanoma: given Australia's modest population, this is better expressed as 59.6 new cases per 100,000 population per year; >1 in 10 of all new cancer cases were melanomas.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] In the United States, about 8-9,000 people die from melanoma a year, and the death rate from melanoma is 1.40 deaths per 100,000 people.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] The incidence of melanoma in the United States increased from 8.8 cases per 100,000 people in 1975 to 27.7 cases per 100,000 people in 2021.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] The annual mortality from melanoma decreased 6.1% annually from 2013 to 2017 and 1.4% annually from 2017 to 2022.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] Advances in treatment are believed to have caused the rapid decline in mortality over the last decade.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] In 2024, in the United States, there were 100,640 cases of melanoma and 8290 deaths.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] There were also 107,240 cases of melanoma in situ, in which melanoma is confined to the epidermis.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] Melanoma is more than 20 times more common in whites than in African Americans.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] Overall, the lifetime risk of getting melanoma is about 2.5% (1 in 40) for whites, 0.1% (1 in 1,000) for African Americans, and 0.5% (1 in 200) for Mexicans.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] The risk of melanoma increases as people age.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] The average age of people when the disease is diagnosed is 63.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] 80% of all cases of melanoma (globally) are diagnosed in people older than 50 years.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] Although melanoma is not a new disease, evidence for its occurrence in antiquity is rather scarce.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] However, one example lies in a 1960s examination of nine Peruvian mummies, radiocarbon dated to be approximately 2400 years old, which showed apparent signs of melanoma: melanotic masses in the skin and diffuse metastases to the bones.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] John Hunter is reported to be the first to operate on metastatic melanoma in 1787.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] Although not knowing precisely what it was, he described it as a "cancerous fungous excrescence".
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] The excised tumor was preserved in the Hunterian Museum of the Royal College of Surgeons of England.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] It was not until 1968 that microscopic examination of the specimen revealed it to be an example of metastatic melanoma.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] The French physician René Laennec was the first to describe melanoma as a disease entity.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] His report was initially presented during a lecture for the Faculté de Médecine de Paris in 1804 and then published as a bulletin in 1806.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] The first English-language report of melanoma was presented by an English general practitioner from Stourbridge, William Norris, in 1820.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] In his later work in 1857 he remarked that there is a familial predisposition for development of melanoma (*Eight Cases of Melanosis with Pathological and Therapeutical Remarks on That Disease*).
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] Norris was also a pioneer in suggesting a link between nevi and melanoma and the possibility of a relationship between melanoma and environmental exposures, by observing that most of his patients had pale complexions.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] He also described that melanomas could be amelanotic and later showed the metastatic nature of melanoma by observing that they can disseminate to other visceral organs.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] The first formal acknowledgment of advanced melanoma as untreatable came from Samuel Cooper in 1840.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] More than one and a half centuries later, this situation remains largely unchanged.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] The word *melanoma* came to English from 19th-century Neo-Latin and uses combining forms derived from ancient Greek roots: *melano-* (denoting melanin) + *-oma* (denoting a tissue mass and especially a neoplasm), in turn from Greek μέλας *melas*, "dark", and -ωμα *oma*, "process".
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] Terms such as "benign melanocytic tumor" unequivocally label the benign types, and modern histopathologic tumor classifications used in medicine do not use the word for benign tumors.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] Pharmacotherapy research for un-resectable or metastatic melanoma is ongoing.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] In clinical research, adoptive cell therapy and gene therapy, are being tested.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] Two kinds of experimental treatments developed at the National Cancer Institute (NCI) have been used in metastatic melanoma with tentative success.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] The first treatment involves adoptive cell therapy (ACT) using TILs, immune cells (tumor-infiltrating lymphocytes) isolated from a person's own melanoma tumor.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] These cells are grown in large numbers in a laboratory and returned to the patient after a treatment that temporarily reduces normal T cells in the patient's body.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] TIL therapy following lymphodepletion can result in durable complete response in a variety of setups.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] The second treatment, adoptive transfer of genetically altered autologous lymphocytes, depends on delivering genes that encode so-called T cell receptors (TCRs) into the patient's lymphocytes.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] After that manipulation, lymphocytes recognize and bind to certain molecules found on the surface of melanoma cells and kill them.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] A cancer vaccine showed modest benefit in late-stage testing in 2009 against melanoma.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] About 60% of melanomas contain a mutation in the B-Raf gene.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] Early clinical trials suggested that B-Raf inhibitors including Plexxicon's vemurafenib could lead to substantial tumor regression in a majority of patients if their tumor contain the B-Raf mutation.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] In June 2011, a large clinical trial confirmed the positive findings from those earlier trials.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] In August 2011, Vemurafenib received FDA approval for the treatment of late-stage melanoma.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] In May 2013, the US FDA approved dabrafenib as a single-agent treatment for patients with BRAF V600E mutation-positive advanced melanoma.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] Some researchers believe that combination therapies that simultaneously block multiple pathways may improve efficacy by making it more difficult for the tumor cells to mutate before being destroyed.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] In October 2012, a study reported that combining Dabrafenib with a MEK inhibitor trametinib led to even better outcomes.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] Compared to Dabrafenib alone, progression-free survival was increased to 41% from 9%, and the median progression-free survival increased to 9.4 months versus 5.8 months.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] Some side effects were, however, increased in the combined study.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] In January 2014, the FDA approved the combination of dabrafenib and trametinib for the treatment of people with BRAF V600E/K-mutant metastatic melanoma.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] In June 2018, the FDA approved the combination of a BRAF inhibitor encorafenib and a MEK inhibitor binimetinib for the treatment of un-resectable or metastatic melanoma with a BRAF V600E or V600K mutation.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] Eventual resistance to BRAF and MEK inhibitors may be due to a cell surface protein known as EphA2 which is now being investigated.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] At the American Society of Clinical Oncology Conference in June 2010, the Bristol Myers Squibb pharmaceutical company reported the clinical findings of their drug ipilimumab.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] The study found an increase in median survival from 6.4 to 10 months in patients with advanced melanomas treated with the monoclonal ipilimumab, versus an experimental vaccine.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] It also found a one-year survival rate of 25% in the control group using the vaccine, 44% in the vaccine and ipilimumab group, and 46% in the group treated with ipilimumab alone.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] However, some have raised concerns about this study for its use of the unconventional control arm, rather than comparing the drug against a placebo or standard treatment.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] The criticism was that although Ipilimumab performed better than the vaccine, the vaccine has not been tested before and may be causing toxicity, making the drug appear better by comparison.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] Ipilimumab was approved by the FDA in March 2011 to treat patients with late-stage melanoma that has spread or cannot be removed by surgery.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] In June 2011, a clinical trial of ipilimumab plus dacarbazine combined this immune system booster with the standard chemotherapy drug that targets cell division.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] It showed an increase in median survival for these late-stage patients to 11 months instead of the 9 months normally seen.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] Researchers were also hopeful of improving the five-year survival rate, though serious adverse side effects were seen in some patients.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] Advances in high-resolution ultrasound scanning have enabled surveillance of metastatic burden to the sentinel lymph nodes.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] The Screening and Surveillance of Ultrasound in Melanoma trial (SUNMEL) is evaluating ultrasound as an alternative to invasive surgical methods.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] In some countries, oncolytic virotherapy methods are studied and used to treat melanoma.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] Oncolytic virotherapy is a promising branch of virotherapy, where oncolytic viruses are used to treat diseases; viruses can increase metabolism, reduce anti-tumor immunity, and disorganize vasculature.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] Talimogene laherparepvec (T-VEC) (which is a herpes simplex virus type 1–derived oncolytic immunotherapy), was shown to be useful against metastatic melanoma in 2015 with an increased survival of 4.4 months.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] Antiretrovirals have been tested in vitro against melanoma.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] The rationale behind this lies in their potential to inhibit human endogenous retroviruses, whose activity has been associated with the development of melanoma.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] Evidence from studies on melanoma cell lines indicates that antiretroviral drugs, including lamivudine, doravirine, and cabotegravir, can effectively downregulate the expression of human endogenous retroviruses (HERV-K).
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] These drugs not only reduce cell growth and invasiveness but also enhance the potential of immune checkpoint therapies.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] Furthermore, they have shown promise in addressing resistance mechanisms that emerge following prolonged treatment with BRAF inhibitors like dabrafenib and AZ628.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] By restoring apoptosis, decreasing cell viability, and influencing tumor suppressor proteins, these antiretrovirals offer a compelling strategy to tackle therapeutic resistance in melanoma.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] Further developments are awaited through animal model testing.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] Recent research has identified miR-139-5p, a small noncoding RNA, as a potential tumor suppressor in melanoma.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] Overexpression of miR-139-5p has been shown to inhibit cell proliferation, migration, and invasion while inducing apoptosis in melanoma cells.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] These effects are associated with the downregulation of IGF1R, a receptor that activates the PI3K/AKT signaling pathway.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] By suppressing IGF1R-mediated signaling, miR-139-5p reduces melanoma cell aggressiveness.
[src:melanoma/melanoma-p02] These findings highlight miR-139-5p as a potential therapeutic agent and emphasize the significance of miRNA regulation in melanoma development and treatment.
